==General description==
{{further|Characteristics of common wasps and bees}}

Bumblebees vary in appearance, but are generally plump and densely furry. They are larger, broader and stouter-bodied than honeybees, and their abdomen tip is more rounded. Many species have broad bands of colour, the patterns helping to distinguish different species. Whereas honeybees have short tongues and therefore mainly pollinate open flowers, some bumblebee species have long tongues and collect nectar from flowers that are closed into a tube.<ref>{{cite web |title=The differences between bumblebees and honeybees |url=http://bumblebeeconservation.org/about-bees/faqs/honeybees-vs-bumblebees/ |publisher=Bumblebee Conservation Trust |accessdate=23 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150228004017/http://bumblebeeconservation.org/about-bees/faqs/honeybees-vs-bumblebees |archive-date=28 February 2015 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Bumblebees have fewer stripes (or none), and usually have part of the body covered in black fur, while honeybees have many stripes including several grey stripes on the abdomen.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wild |first1=Alex |title=How to tell the difference between honey bees and bumble bees |url=http://www.myrmecos.net/2011/10/11/how-to-tell-the-difference-between-honey-bees-and-bumble-bees/ |publisher=Myrmecos |accessdate=23 February 2015|date=2011-10-11 }}</ref> Sizes are very variable even within species; the largest British species, ''B. terrestris'', has queens up to {{cvt|22|mm|1}} long, males up to {{cvt|16|mm|1}} long, and workers between {{cvt|11|and(-)|17|mm|1}} long.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bumblebee species|url=http://www.bumblebee.org/key.htm |publisher=Bumblebee.org |accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref> The largest bumblebee species in the world is ''[[Bombus dahlbomii|B. dahlbomii]]'' of Chile, up to about {{cvt|40|mm|1}} long, and described as "flying mice" and "a monstrous fluffy ginger beast".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Johnston |first1=Ian |title=Bye bye big bee: In South America, the world's largest bumblebee is at risk from imported rivals |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/environment/nature/bye-bye-big-bee-in-south-america-the-worlds-largest-bumblebee-is-at-risk-from-imported-rivals-9587240.html |publisher=The Independent |accessdate=23 February 2015 |date=6 July 2014}}</ref> 

==Distribution and habitat==

Bumblebees are typically found in [[temperate climate]]s, and are often found at higher [[latitude]]s and [[altitude]]s than other bees, although a few lowland [[tropics|tropical]] species exist.<ref>{{cite web |title=Map at: Bumblebees of the world |publisher=[[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]] |url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/research-curation/projects/bombus/introduction.html |accessdate=9 July 2007}}</ref> A few species (''[[Bombus polaris|B. polaris]]'' and ''[[Bombus alpinus|B. alpinus]]'') range into very cold climates where other bees might not be found; ''B. polaris'' occurs in northern [[Ellesmere Island]] in the high Arctic, along with another bumblebee ''[[Bombus hyperboreus|B. hyperboreus]]'', which parasitises its nest. This is the most northernmost occurrence of any eusocial insect.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Milliron, H. E. |author2=Oliver, D. R. |year=1966 |title=Bumblebees from northern Ellesmere Island, with observations on usurpation by ''Megabombus hyperboreus'' (Schönh.) |journal=Canadian Entomologist |volume=98 |issue=2 |pages=207–213 |doi=10.4039/Ent98207-2}}</ref> One reason for their presence in cold places is that bumblebees can regulate their [[Thermoregulation|body temperature]], via [[sunlight|solar radiation]], internal mechanisms of "shivering" and radiative cooling from the abdomen (called [[heterothermy]]). Other bees have similar [[physiology]], but the mechanisms seem best developed and have been most studied in bumblebees.<ref name=Heinrich>{{cite book |author=Heinrich, B. |year=1981 |title=Insect Thermoregulation |publisher=Krieger Publishing Company |isbn=978-0-471-05144-2}}</ref>  They adapt to higher elevations by extending their wing stroke amplitude.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Dillon |first=Michael E |author2=Dudley, Robert |title=Surpassing Mt. Everest: extreme flight performance of alpine bumble-bees |journal=Biology Letters |date=February 2014 |volume=10 |issue=2 |page=20130922 |doi=10.1098/rsbl.2013.0922 |pmid=24501268 |pmc=3949368}}</ref> Bumblebees have a largely [[cosmopolitan distribution]] but are absent from Australia (apart from Tasmania where they have been introduced) and are found in Africa only north of the Sahara.<ref name=BugGuide>{{cite web |title=Genus ''Bombus'' – Bumble Bees |url=http://bugguide.net/node/view/3077 |website=BugGuide.Net |accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref> More than a hundred years ago they have also been introduced to New Zealand, where they play an important role as efficient pollinators.{{cn|date=November 2018}}

==Biology==
[[File:Bumblebee heuchera.jpg|thumb|right|upright|A common carder bumblebee ''[[Bombus pascuorum]]'' extending its tongue towards a ''[[Heuchera]]'' [[inflorescence]]]]

===Feeding===
The bumblebee tongue (the [[proboscis]]) is a long, hairy structure that extends from a sheath-like modified maxilla. The primary action of the tongue is lapping, that is, repeated dipping of the tongue into liquid.<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1007/BF00377639 | pmid = 28311376 | author = Harder, L.D. | year = 1986 | title = Effects of nectar concentration and flower depth on flower handling efficiency of bumble bees | url = | journal = Oecologia | volume = 69 | issue = 2| pages = 309–315 | bibcode = 1986Oecol..69..309H }}</ref> 
The tip of the tongue probably acts as a suction cup and during lapping, nectar may be drawn up the proboscis by [[capillary action]]. When at rest or flying, the proboscis is kept folded under the head. The longer the tongue, the deeper the bumblebee can probe into a flower and bees probably learn by experience which flower source is best-suited to their tongue length.<ref>{{cite book|author=Heinrich, Bernd |title=Bumblebee Economics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=73yeOpls5qsC&pg=PA152|year=2004 |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=978-0-674-01639-2 |page=152}}</ref> Bees with shorter proboscides, like [[Bombus bifarius]], have a more difficult time foraging nectar relative to other bumblebees with longer proboscides; to overcome this disadvantage, B. bifarius workers were observed to lick the back of spurs on the nectar duct, which resulted in a small reward.<ref>{{Cite journal|jstor= 3548471|title = Effects of nectar robbing on nectar dynamics and bumblebee foraging strategies in Linaria vulgaris (Scrophulariaceae)|last = Newman|first = Daniel A.|year= 2005|journal = Okies|doi =10.1111/j.0030-1299.2005.13884.x |last2 = Thomson|first2 = James D.|last3 = Ranta|first3 = Esa|volume = 10|issue = 2|pages = 309–320}}</ref>

===Wax production===
The exoskeleton of the [[abdomen]] is divided into plates called dorsal [[tergum|tergites]] and ventral [[Sternum (arthropod anatomy)|sternites]]. Wax is secreted from [[gland]]s on the abdomen and extruded between the sternites where it resembles flakes of [[dandruff]]. It is secreted by the queen when she starts a nest and by young workers. It is scraped from the abdomen by the legs, moulded until malleable and used in the construction of honeypots, to cover the eggs, to line empty cocoons for use as storage containers and sometimes to cover the exterior of the nest.<ref name=body>{{cite web |url=http://www.bumblebee.org/body.htm |title=The bumblebee body |publisher=Bumblebee.org |accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref>

===Coloration===
[[File:Bombus.barbutellus.-.lindsey.jpg|thumb|upright|Cuckoo bumblebees, like this ''[[Bombus barbutellus]]'', have similar [[aposematic]] (warning) coloration to nest-making bumblebees, and may also [[mimicry|mimic]] their host species.]]
{{further|aposematism|mimicry}}

The brightly coloured pile of the bumblebee is an [[aposematism|aposematic]] (warning) signal, given that females can inflict a painful sting. Depending on the species and [[polymorphism (biology)|morph]], the warning colours range from entirely black, to bright yellow, red, orange, white, and pink.<ref name=Williams2007>{{cite journal |author=Williams, Paul H. |year=2007 |title=The distribution of bumblebee colour patterns world-wide: possible significance for thermoregulation, crypsis, and warning mimicry |journal=Biological Journal of the Linnean Society |volume=92 |issue=1 |pages=97–118 |url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/research-curation/projects/bombus/colour.html |accessdate=9 July 2007 |doi=10.1111/j.1095-8312.2007.00878.x}}</ref> [[Diptera]]n flies in the families [[Syrphidae]] (hoverflies), [[Asilidae]] (robber flies), [[Tabanidae]] (horseflies), [[Oestridae]] (bot or warble flies) and [[Bombyliidae]] (bee flies) all include [[Batesian mimics]] of bumblebees, resembling them closely enough to deceive at least some predators.<ref name="ThorpHorning1983"/>

Many  species of ''Bombus'', including the group sometimes called ''Psithyrus'' (cuckoo bumblebees), have evolved [[Müllerian mimicry]], where the different bumblebees in a region resemble each other, so that a young predator need only learn to avoid any of them once. For example, in California a group of bumblebees consists of largely black species including ''[[Bombus californicus|B. californicus]]'', ''[[Bombus caliginosus|B. caliginosus]]'', ''[[Bombus vandykeei|B. vandykei]]'', ''[[Bombus vosnesenskii|B. vosnesenskii]]'', ''[[Bombus insularis|B. insularis]]'' and ''[[Bombus fernaldae|B. fernaldae]]''. Other bees in California include a group of species all banded black and yellow. In each case, Müllerian mimicry provides the bees in the group with a selective advantage.<ref name="ThorpHorning1983">{{cite book |last1=Thorp |first1=Robbin W. |last2=Horning |first2=Donald S. |last3=Dunning |first3=Lorry L. |title=Bumble Bees and Cuckoo Bumble Bees of California (Hymenoptera, Apidae) |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v1eJ3fWwshIC&pg=PA9 |year=1983 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=978-0-520-09645-5 |page=9}}</ref> In addition, parasitic (cuckoo) bumblebees resemble their hosts more closely than would be expected by chance, at least in areas like Europe where parasite-host co-speciation is common; but this too may be explained as Müllerian mimicry, rather than requiring the parasite's coloration to deceive the host ([[aggressive mimicry]]).<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Williams |first1=Paul H. |title=Do the parasitic Psithyrus resemble their host bumblebees in colour pattern? |journal=Apidologie |date=2008 |volume=39 |issue=6 |pages=637–649 |doi=10.1051/apido:2008048 |url=http://www.apidologie.org/articles/apido/pdf/2008/06/m08010.pdf}}</ref>

===Temperature control===
Bumblebees are active in conditions when honeybees stay at home, and can readily absorb heat from even weak sunshine.<ref name="Macdonald, 2003. p. 6">Macdonald, 2003. p. 6</ref> The thick pile created by long [[seta]]e (bristles) acts as insulation to keep bumblebees warm in cold weather; species from cold climates have longer setae (and thus thicker insulation) than those from the tropics.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Peat, J. |author2=Darvill, B. |author3=Ellis, J. |author4=Goulson, D. |title=Effects of climate on intra- and interspecific size variation in bumble-bees |journal=Ecology |date=2005 |volume=19 |pages=145–151 |url=https://www.sussex.ac.uk/webteam/gateway/file.php?name=peat-et-al-funct-ecol-2005.pdf&site=411 |doi=10.1111/j.0269-8463.2005.00946.x}}</ref> The temperature of the flight muscles, which occupy much of the thorax, needs to be at least {{convert|30|°C}} before flight can take place. The muscle temperature can be raised by shivering. It takes about five minutes for the muscles to reach this temperature at an air temperature of {{convert|13|°C}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bumblebee.org/bodyWing.htm |title=Bumblebee wings |publisher=Bumblebee.org |accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref>

==== Chill-coma temperature ====
The chill-coma temperature in relation to flying insects is the temperature at which flight muscles cannot be activated. Compared to honey bees and carpenter bees, bumblebees have the lowest chill-coma temperature. Of the bumblebees ''[[Two-spotted bumble bee|Bombus bimaculatus]]'' has the lowest at {{convert|7|°C}}. However, bumblebees have been seen to fly in colder ambient temperatures. This discrepancy is likely because the chill-coma temperature was determined by tests done in a laboratory setting. However, bumblebees live in insulated shelters and can shiver to warm up before venturing into the cold.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Comparative Study of Chill-Coma Temperatures and Muscle Potentials in Insect Flight Muscles|url = http://jeb.biologists.org/content/150/1/221|journal = Journal of Experimental Biology|date = May 1990|issn = 0022-0949|pages = 221–231|volume = 150|issue = 1|first = Franz|last = Goller|first2 = Harald|last2 = Esch}}</ref>

===Communication and social learning===
Bumblebees do not have ears, and it is not known whether or how well they can hear. However, they are sensitive to the vibrations made by sound travelling through wood or other materials.<ref name=body/>

Bumblebees do not exhibit the "[[Waggle dance|bee dances]]" used by honeybees to tell other workers the locations of food sources. Instead, when they return from a successful foraging expedition, they run excitedly around in the nest for several minutes before going out to forage once more. These bees may be offering some form of communication based on the buzzing sounds made by their wings, which may stimulate other bees to start foraging.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Dornhaus, Anna |author2=Chittka, Lars |year=2001 |title=Food alert in bumblebees (''Bombus terrestris''): possible mechanisms and evolutionary implications |journal=Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology |volume=50 |issue=6 |pages=570–576 |doi=10.1007/s002650100395 }}</ref> Another stimulant to foraging activity is the level of food reserves in the colony. Bees monitor the amount of honey in the honeypots, and when little is left or when high quality food is added, they are more likely to go out to forage.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Dornhaus, Anna |author2=Chittka, Lars |year=2005 |title=Bumble bees (''Bombus terrestris'') store both food and information in honeypots |journal=Behavioral Ecology |volume=16 |issue=3 |pages=661–666 |doi= 10.1093/beheco/ari040 }}</ref>

Bumblebees have been observed to partake in [[social learning in animals|social learning]]. In a 2017 study involving ''[[Bombus terrestris]]'', bees were taught to complete an unnatural task of moving large objects to obtain a reward. Bees that first observed another bee complete the task were significantly more successful in learning the task than bees that observed the same action performed by a magnet, indicating the importance of social information. The bees did not copy each other exactly: in fact, the study suggested that the bees were instead attempting to [[Emulation (observational learning)|emulate each other's goals]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Loukola|first1=Olli J.|last2=Perry|first2=Clint J.|last3=Coscos|first3=Louie|last4=Chittka|first4=Lars|title=Bumblebees show cognitive flexibility by improving on an observed complex behavior|journal=Science|date=24 February 2017|volume=355|issue=6327|pages=833–836|doi=10.1126/science.aag2360|pmid=28232576|url=http://science.sciencemag.org/content/355/6327/833|language=en|issn=0036-8075|bibcode=2017Sci...355..833L}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Watson|first1=Traci|title=Bees learn football from their buddies|url=http://www.nature.com/news/bees-learn-football-from-their-buddies-1.21540|journal=Nature News|language=en|doi=10.1038/nature.2017.21540|year=2017}}</ref>

===Reproduction and nesting===
[[File:Bumblebee nest.jpg|thumb|Nest of red-tailed bumblebee. ''[[Bombus lapidarius]]'', showing [[wax]] pots full of honey]]
{{further|haplodiploidy|worker policing}}

Nest size depends on species of bumblebee. Most form [[colony (biology)|colonies]] of between 50 and 400 individuals,<ref name="BBCT-nest"/> but colonies have been documented as small as ~20 individuals and as large as 1700.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cueva del Castillo|first1=R|last2=Sanabria-Urbán|first2=S.|last3=Serrano-Meneses|first3=M. A.|year=2015|title=Trade-offs in the evolution of bumblebee colony and body size: a comparative analysis|journal=Ecology and Evolution|volume=5|issue=18|pages=3914–3926|pmid=26445652|pmc=4588658|doi=10.1002/ece3.1659}}</ref> These nests are small compared to honeybee hives, which hold about 50,000 bees. Many species nest underground, choosing old [[rodent]] burrows or sheltered places, and avoiding places that receive direct sunlight that could result in overheating. Other species make nests above ground, whether in thick grass or in holes in trees. A bumblebee nest is not organised into hexagonal combs like that of a honeybee; the cells are instead clustered together untidily. The workers remove dead bees or larvae from the nest and deposit them outside the nest entrance, helping to prevent disease. Nests in temperate regions last only for a single season and do not survive the winter.<ref name="BBCT-nest">{{cite web|title=Bumblebee nests|url=http://bumblebeeconservation.org/about-bees/habitats/bumblebee-nests/|publisher=Bumblebee Conservation Trust|accessdate=13 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922230805/https://bumblebeeconservation.org/about-bees/habitats/bumblebee-nests/|archive-date=22 September 2017|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

In the early spring, the queen comes out of [[diapause]] and finds a suitable place to create her colony. Then she builds wax cells in which to lay her eggs which were fertilised the previous year. The eggs that hatch develop into female workers, and in time, the queen populates the colony, with workers feeding the young and performing other duties similar to honeybee workers. In [[Temperate climate|temperate zone]]s, young queens ([[gyne]]s) leave the nest in the autumn and [[mating|mate]], often more than once, with males ([[drone (bee)|drone]]s) that are forcibly driven out of the colony.<ref name="Goulson-cycle"/> The drones and workers die as the weather turns colder; the young queens feed intensively to build up stores of fat for the winter. They survive in a resting state (diapause), generally below ground, until the weather warms up in the spring with the [[early bumblebee]] being the species that is among the first to emerge.<ref name="Goulson-cycle"/><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Using citizen science to monitor Bombus populations in the UK: nesting ecology and relative abundance in the urban environment|journal = Journal of Insect Conservation|date=November 2011|issn = 1366-638X|pages = 697–707|volume = 16|issue = 5|doi = 10.1007/s10841-011-9450-3|first = Gillian C.|last = Lye|first2 = Juliet L.|last2 = Osborne|first3 = Kirsty J.|last3 = Park|first4 = Dave|last4 = Goulson}}</ref><ref name="BBCT-lifecycle">{{cite web |title=The Bumblebee Lifecycle |url=http://bumblebeeconservation.org/about-bees/lifecycle/ |publisher=Bumblebee Conservation Trust |accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref> Many species of bumblebee follow this general trend within the year. ''[[Bombus pensylvanicus]]'' is a species that follows this type of colony cycle.<ref name="bioweb">{{cite web|title=Bombus pensylvanicus|url=http://bioweb.uwlax.edu/bio210/s2013/netwal_meli/reproduction.htm|publisher=University of Wisconsin La Crosse|year= 2013}}</ref> For this species the cycle begins in February, reproduction starts in July or August, and ends in the winter months. The queen remains in hibernation until spring of the following year in order to optimize conditions to search for a nest.<ref name = "juan">{{cite journal |author=Juan Di Trani de la Hoz |title= Phenology of Bombus pennsylvanicus sonorus Say (Hymenoptera: Apidae) in Central Mexico |journal= Neotropical Entomology |volume=35 |issue=5 |pages= |year=2006 |doi=10.1590/S1519-566X2006000500004|url= http://www.scielo.br/scielo.php?script=sci_arttext&pid=S1519-566X2006000500004 }}</ref>

<!--[[File:Bumble bee nest hole.JPG|thumb|left|upright|A queen buff-tailed bumblebee, ''[[Bombus terrestris]]'', digging a nest hole]]-->
[[File:Nest of the Common Humble-Bee Plate 15 Jardine.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.2|Bumblebee life-cycle showing adults and [[larvae]] in nest of ''B. terrestris''. Engraved in 1840 by [[William Home Lizars]] after drawing probably by [[James Hope Stewart]].<ref>'Nest of the Common Humble-Bee (B. terrestris)', Plate 15 from [[Sir William Jardine, 7th Baronet#The Naturalist's Library|The Naturalist's Library]], Vol. VI. ''Entomology'', by [[Sir William Jardine, 7th Baronet|Sir William Jardine]]. Edinburgh: W. H. Lizars, 1840</ref>]]

In fertilised queens, the ovaries only become active when the queen starts to lay. An egg passes along the [[oviduct]] to the vagina where there is a chamber called the [[spermatheca]], in which the sperm from the mating is stored. Depending on need, she may allow her egg to be fertilised. Unfertilised eggs become [[haploid]] males; fertilised eggs grow into [[diploid]] females and queens.<ref name="NZ-bees">{{cite web |title=Biology |url=http://www.biobees.co.nz/biology.html |publisher=Biobees Bumblebee Pollination |accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref> The [[hormone]]s that stimulate the development of the ovaries are suppressed in female worker bees, while the queen remains dominant.<ref name="Goulson-cycle"/>

To develop, the [[larva]]e must be fed both nectar for [[carbohydrate]]s and pollen for [[protein]]. Bumblebees feed nectar to the larvae by chewing a small hole in the brood cell into which they regurgitate nectar. Larvae are fed pollen in one of two ways, depending on the bumblebee species. Pocket-making bumblebees create pockets of pollen at the base of the brood-cell clump from which the larvae feed themselves. Pollen-storing bumblebees keep pollen in separate wax pots and feed it to the larvae.<ref name="Evans">{{cite book |title=Befriending Bumble Bees |author1=Evans, Elaine |author2=Burns, Ian |author3=Spivak, Marla |year=2007 |publisher=[[University of Minnesota Press]] |location=St. Paul}}</ref>

[[File:Apoidea.jpg|thumb|An above-ground nest, hidden in grass and moss, of the common carder bee, ''[[Bombus pascuorum]]''. The wax canopy or involucrum has been removed to show winged [[worker (bee)|workers]] and [[pupae]] in irregularly placed wax cells.]]
After the emergence of the first or second group of offspring, workers take over the task of foraging and the queen spends most of her time laying eggs and caring for larvae. The colony grows progressively larger and eventually begins to produce males and new queens.<ref name="Goulson-cycle">Goulson, 2013. pp. 16–24</ref>
Bumblebee workers can lay unfertilised haploid eggs (with only a single set of [[chromosome]]s) that develop into viable male bumblebees. Only fertilised queens can lay diploid eggs (one set of chromosomes from a drone, one from the queen) that mature into workers and new queens.<ref>Goulson, 2013. pp. 108–114</ref>

In a young colony, the queen minimises reproductive competition from workers by suppressing their egg-laying through physical aggression and [[pheromone]]s.<ref name="Honk">{{cite journal |last1=Van Honk |first1=C. G. J. |last2=Velthuis |first2=H. H. W. |last3=Röseler |first3=P.-F. |last4=Malotaux |first4=M. E. |year=1980 |title=The mandibular glands of ''Bombus terrestris'' queens as a source of queen pheromones |journal=Entomologia Experimentalis et Applicata |volume=28 |issue=2 |pages=191–198 |doi=10.1007/BF00287128}}</ref> [[Worker policing]] leads to nearly all eggs laid by workers being eaten.<ref name=Zanette/> Thus, the queen is usually the mother of all of the first males laid. Workers eventually begin to lay male eggs later in the season when the queen's ability to suppress their reproduction diminishes.<ref name="Fletcher">{{cite journal |author1=Fletcher, D. J. C. |author2=Fletcher, Ross K. |year=1985 |title=Regulation of reproduction in eusocial Hymenoptera |journal=Annual Review of Entomology |volume=30 |pages=319–343 |doi=10.1146/annurev.en.30.010185.001535}}</ref> Because of the reproductive [[competition (biology)|competition]] between workers and the queen, bumblebees are considered "primitively eusocial".<ref name=Cardinal/><ref name=Zanette>{{cite journal |last1=Zanette |first1=L. R. |last2=Miller |first2=S. D. |last3=Faria |first3=C. M.|last4=Almond |first4=E. J. |last5=Huggins |first5=T. J.|last6=Jordan |first6=W. C. |last7=Bourke |first7=A. F. |title=Reproductive conflict in bumblebees and the evolution of worker policing |journal=Evolution |date=December 2012 |volume=66 |issue=12 |pages=3765–3777 |doi=10.1111/j.1558-5646.2012.01709.x |pmid=23206135 }}</ref>

Although a large majority of bumblebees follow such monogynous colony cycles that only involve one queen, some select Bombus species (such as ''[[Bombus atratus]]'') will spend part of their life cycle in a polygynous phase (have multiple queens in one nest during these periods of polygyny).<ref name=three>{{cite journal|last1=Cameron|first1=S.D|title=Mediators of dominance and   reproductive success  among queens in the cyclically polygynous neotropical bumble bee Bombus atratus Franklin|journal=Insectes Sociaux|year=1998|volume=45|issue=2|pages=135–149|url=http://www.life.illinois.edu/scameron/pdfs/Mediators%20of%20dominance%20and%20reproductive%20success.pdf|format=PDF|accessdate=27 September 2015|doi=10.1007/s000400050075}}</ref>

===Foraging behaviour===
{{further|Bumblebee communication|nectar robbing}}
[[File:Bumblebee 05.JPG|thumb|left|A bumblebee loaded with [[pollen]] in its [[pollen basket]]s]]

Bumblebees generally visit flowers that exhibit the bee [[pollination syndrome]] and these patches of flowers may be up to 1–2&nbsp;km from their colony.<ref name="Walther-Hellwig">{{cite journal |author1=Walther-Hellwig, K. |author2=Frankl, R. |year=2000 |title=Foraging distances of ''Bombus muscorum'', ''Bombus lapidarius'', and ''Bombus terrestris'' (Hymenoptera, Apidae) |journal=Journal of Insect Behavior |volume=13 |issue=2 |pages=239–246 |doi=10.1023/A:1007740315207}}</ref> They tend to visit the same patches of flowers every day, as long as they continue to find nectar and pollen there,<ref name="Dramstad">{{cite journal |author1=Dramstad, W. E. |author2=Fry, G. L. A. |author3=Schaffer, M. J. |year=2003 |title=Bumblebee foraging—is closer really better? |journal=Agriculture, Ecosystems and Environment |volume=95 |issue=1 |pages=349–357 |doi=10.1016/S0167-8809(02)00043-9}}</ref> a habit known as pollinator or [[flower constancy]]. While foraging, bumblebees can reach ground speeds of up to {{convert|15|m/s|km/h|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Osborne, J. L. |author2=Clark, S. J. |author3=Morris, R. J. |author4=Williams, I. H. |author5=Riley, J. R. |author6=Smith, A. D. |author7=Reynolds, D. R. |author8=Edwards, A. S. |year=1999 |title=A landscape-scale study of bumble bee foraging range and constancy, using harmonic radar |journal=Journal of Applied Ecology |volume=36 |issue=4 |pages=519–533 |doi=10.1046/j.1365-2664.1999.00428.x}}</ref>

Bumblebees use a combination of colour and spatial relationships to learn which flowers to forage from.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Blackawton, P. S. |author2= Airzee, S. |author3= Allen, A. |author4=Baker, S. |author5= Berrow, A. |author6= Blair, C. |author7= Churchill, M. |author8= Coles R. F.-J. |author9=Cumming, L. |others=Fraquelli, C. Hackford, A. Hinton Mellor, M. Hutchcroft, B. Ireland, J.; Jewsbury, D.; Littlejohns, A.;  Littlejohns,G. M.; Lotto, M.; McKeown, J.; O'Toole, A.; Richards, H.; Robbins-Davey, L.; Roblyn, S.; Rodwell-Lynn, H.; Schenck, D.; Springer, J.; Wishy, A.; Rodwell-Lynn, T.; Strudwick, D.; Lotto, R. B. |displayauthors=9 |year=2010 |title=Blackawton bees |journal=Biology Letters |volume=7 |issue=2 |pages=168–72 |pmid=21177694 |pmc=3061190 |doi=10.1098/rsbl.2010.1056 |accessdate=5 January 2011 |url=http://rsbl.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/early/2010/12/18/rsbl.2010.1056 |last10=Fraquelli |first10=L. |last11=Hackford |first11=C. |last12=Hinton Mellor |first12=A. |last13=Hutchcroft |first13=M. |last14=Ireland |first14=B. |last15=Jewsbury |first15=D. |last16=Littlejohns |first16=A. |last17=Littlejohns |first17=G. M. |last18=Lotto |first18=M. |last19=McKeown |first19=J. |last20=O'Toole |first20=A. |last21=Richards |first21=H. |last22=Robbins-Davey |first22=L. |last23=Roblyn |first23=S. |last24=Rodwell-Lynn |first24=H. |last25=Schenck |first25=D. |last26=Springer |first26=J. |last27=Wishy |first27=A. |last28=Rodwell-Lynn |first28=T. |last29=Strudwick |first29=D. |last30=Lotto |first30=R. B.}}</ref>  They can also [[electroreception|detect]] both the presence and the pattern of electric fields on flowers, which occur due to [[atmospheric electricity]], and take a while to leak away into the ground. They use this information to find out if a flower has been recently visited by another bee.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Detection and Learning of Floral Electric Fields by Bumblebees |year=2013 |last1=Clarke |first1=D. |last2=Whitney |first2=H.|last3=Sutton |first3=G. |last4=Robert |first4=D. |journal=Science |doi=10.1126/science.1230883 |laysummary=http://www.nature.com/news/bumblebees-sense-electric-fields-in-flowers-1.12480 |laysource=Nature News & Comment|laydate=21 February 2013 |volume=340 |issue=6128 |pages=66–9 |pmid=23429701|bibcode = 2013Sci...340...66C }}</ref> Bumblebees can detect the temperature of flowers,<ref>{{cite journal |title=The interaction of temperature and sucrose concentration on foraging preferences in bumblebees |year=2008 |last1=Whitney |first1=H. |last2=Dyer |first2=A.|last3=Rands |first3=S.A. |last4=Glover |first4=B.J. |journal=Naturwissenschaften |doi=10.1007/s00114-008-0393-9|pmid=18523748 |volume=95 |issue=9 |pages=845–850|bibcode=2008NW.....95..845W }}</ref> as well as which parts of the flower are hotter or cooler<ref>{{cite journal |title=The diversity of floral temperature patterns, and their use by pollinators|year=2017 |last1=Harrap |first1=M.J.M. |last2=Rands |first2=S.A.|last3=Hempel de Ibarra |first3=N. |last4=Whitney |first4=H.M. |journal=eLife |doi=10.7554/eLife.31262 |pmid=29254518 |pmc=5736352 |volume=6 }}</ref> and use this information to recognise flowers. After arriving at a flower, they extract nectar using their long tongues ("[[Tongue|glossa]]e") and store it in their [[crop (anatomy)|crop]]s. Many species of bumblebees also exhibit "nectar robbing": instead of inserting the mouthparts into the flower in the normal way, these bees bite directly through the base of the [[Petal#Corolla|corolla]] to extract nectar, avoiding pollen transfer.<ref name="Maloof">{{cite journal |author=Maloof, J. E. |year=2001 |title=The effects of a bumble bee nectar robber on plant reproductive success and pollinator behavior |journal=American Journal of Botany |volume=88 |issue=11 |pages=1960–1965 |doi= 10.2307/3558423|url=http://www.amjbot.org/cgi/content/abstract/88/11/1960 |jstor=3558423 }}</ref>

{{multiple image
