Pollen is removed from flowers deliberately or incidentally by bumblebees. Incidental removal occurs when bumblebees come in contact with the [[stamen|anthers]] of a flower while collecting nectar. When it enters a flower, the bumblebee's body hairs receive a dusting of pollen from the anthers. In queens and workers this is then groomed into the [[Pollen basket|corbiculae]] (pollen baskets) on the hind legs where it can be seen as bulging masses that may contain as many as a million pollen grains. Male bumblebees do not have corbiculae and do not purposively collect pollen.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bumblebee.org/bodyLegs.htm |title=Bumblebee legs |publisher=Bumblebee.org |accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref> Bumblebees are also capable of [[buzz pollination]], in which they dislodge pollen from the anthers by creating a [[resonance|resonant vibration]] with their flight muscles.<ref>{{cite web |title=Buzz Pollination | author=Leonard, Anne |url=http://www.anneleonard.com/buzz-pollination |accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref>

In at least some species, once a bumblebee has visited a flower, it leaves a scent mark on it. This scent mark deters bumblebees from visiting that flower until the scent degrades.<ref name="goulson">{{cite journal |author1=Goulson, Dave |author2=Hawson, Sadie A. |author3=Stout, Jane C. |year=1998 |title=Foraging bumblebees avoid flowers already visited by conspecifics or by other bumblebee species |journal=Animal Behaviour |volume=55 |issue=1 |pages=199–206 |doi=10.1006/anbe.1997.0570 |pmid=9480686}}</ref> This scent mark is a general chemical bouquet that bumblebees leave behind in different locations (e.g. nest, neutral, and food sites),<ref name="saleh">{{cite journal |last1=Saleh |first1=Nehal |first2=Alan G. |last2=Scott |first3=Gareth P. |last3=Bryning |first4=Lars |last4=Chittka |lastauthoramp=yes |year=2007 |title=Bumblebees use incidental footprints to generate adaptive behaviour at flowers and nest |journal=Arthropod-Plant Interactions |volume=1 |issue=2 |pages=119–127 |doi=10.1007/s11829-007-9011-6}}</ref> and they learn to use this bouquet to identify both rewarding and unrewarding flowers,<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Saleh, Nehal |author2=Chittka, Lars |year=2006 |title=The importance of experience in the interpretation of conspecific chemical signals |journal=[[Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology]] |volume=61 |issue=2 |pages=215–220 |doi=10.1007/s00265-006-0252-7}}</ref> and may be able to identify who else has visited a flower.<ref name="pearce">{{cite journal |author1=Pearce, Richard F. |author2=Giuggioli, Luca |author3=Rands, Sean A. |year=2017 |title=Bumblebees can discriminate between scent-marks deposited by conspecifics |journal=Scientific Reports |volume=7 |pages=43872 |doi=10.1038/srep43872 |pmid=28266572 |pmc=5339730|bibcode=2017NatSR...743872P }}</ref> Bumblebees rely on this chemical bouquet more when the flower has a high handling time, that is, where it takes a longer time for the bee to find the nectar once inside the flower.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Saleh |first1=Nehal |first2=Kazuharu |last2=Ohashi |first3=James D. |last3=Thomson |first4=Lars |last4=Chittka  |lastauthoramp=yes |year=2006 |title=Facultative use of repellent scent mark in foraging bumblebees: complex versus simple flowers |journal=Animal Behaviour |volume=71 |issue=4 |pages=847–854 |doi=10.1016/j.anbehav.2005.06.014}}</ref>

Once they have collected nectar and pollen, female workers return to the nest and deposit the harvest into brood cells, or into [[wax]] cells for storage. Unlike honeybees, bumblebees only store a few days' worth of food, so are much more vulnerable to food shortages.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/nature-online/life/plants-fungi/postcode-plants/article.html |title=Living larders for bumblebees |publisher=Natural History Museum |accessdate=20 June 2010 |author1=Comba, Livio |author2=Sarah Corbet }}</ref> Male bumblebees collect only nectar and do so to feed themselves. They may visit quite different flowers from the workers because of their different nutritional needs.<ref>Macdonald, 2003. p. 7</ref>

===Asynchronous flight muscles===

Bees beat their wings about 200 times a second. Their thorax muscles do not contract on each nerve firing, but rather vibrate like a plucked rubber band. This is efficient, since it lets the system consisting of muscle and wing operate at its resonant frequency, leading to low energy consumption. Further, it is necessary, since insect motor nerves generally cannot fire 200 times per second.<ref name="Book of Insect Records">{{cite web|last1=Scherer|first1=C.W.|title=Fastest Wing Beat|url=http://entnemdept.ifas.ufl.edu/walker/ufbir/chapters/chapter_09.shtml|website=Book of Insect Records|publisher=University of Florida|accessdate=29 October 2015}}</ref> These types of muscles are called [[asynchronous muscles]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.amentsoc.org/insects/glossary/terms/asynchronous-muscle | title = Definition of Asynchronous muscle in the Entomologists' glossary |accessdate = 19 April 2013| publisher = Department of Entomology, North Carolina State University}}</ref> and are found in the [[insect wing]] systems in families such as Hymenoptera, Diptera, [[Coleoptera]], and [[Hemiptera]].<ref name="Book of Insect Records"/> Bumblebees must warm up their bodies considerably to get airborne at low ambient temperatures. Bumblebees can reach an internal thoracic temperature of 30&nbsp;°C (86&nbsp;°F) using this method.<ref name=Heinrich/><ref name="Schmidt-Nielsen1997">{{cite book |last=Schmidt-Nielsen |first=Knut |title=Animal Physiology: Adaptation and Environment |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Af7IwQWJoCMC&pg=PA290 |date=10 April 1997 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-57098-5 |pages=290–291}}</ref>

===Cuckoo bumblebees===

[[File:Bumblebee January 2008-4.jpg|thumb|left|The cuckoo bumblebee ''B. vestalis'', a parasite of ''B. terrestris'']]
{{main|Psithyrus}}

Bumblebees of the subgenus ''[[Psithyrus]]'' (known as 'cuckoo bumblebees', and formerly considered a separate genus) are [[brood parasite]]s,<ref name=Erler>{{cite journal |last1=Erler |first1=S. |last2=Lattorff |first2=H. M. G.|title=The degree of parasitism of the bumblebee (Bombus terrestris) by cuckoo bumblebees (Bombus (Psithyrus) vestalis) |journal=Insectes Sociaux |date=2010 |volume=57 |issue=4 |pages=371–377 |doi=10.1007/s00040-010-0093-2 |url=<!--https://www.researchgate.net/profile/H_Michael_Lattorff/publication/225032044_The_degree_of_parasitism_of_the_bumblebee_(Bombus_terrestris)_by_cuckoo_bumblebees_(Bombus_(Psithyrus)_vestalis)/links/0fcfd4fbcbfcb5aed6000000.pdf-->}}</ref> sometimes called [[kleptoparasitism|kleptoparasites]],<ref name="SlaterRosenblatt2005">{{cite book |author1=Peter J.B. Slater |author2=Jay S. Rosenblatt |author3=Charles T. Snowdon |author4=Timothy J. Roper |author5=H. Jane Brockmann |author6=Marc Naguib |title=Advances in the Study of Behavior |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WQl2s_xwfagC&pg=PA365 |date=30 January 2005 |publisher=Academic Press |isbn=978-0-08-049015-1 |page=365}}</ref> in the colonies of other bumblebees, and have lost the ability to collect pollen. Before finding and invading a host colony, a ''Psithyrus'' female, such as that of the ''Psithyrus'' species of ''[[Bombus sylvestris|B. sylvestris]],''<ref>Pierre Rasmont. "''Bombus (Psithyrus) sylvestris'' (Lepeletier, 1832)". Université de Mons. Retrieved 6 January 2013.</ref> feeds directly from flowers. Once she has infiltrated a host colony, the ''Psithyrus'' female kills or subdues the queen of that colony, and uses pheromones and physical attacks to force the workers of that colony to feed her and her young.<ref name=Zimma>{{cite journal |last1=Zimma |first1=B. O. |first2=M. |last2=Ayasse |first3=J. |last3=Tengo |first4=F. |last4=Ibarra |first5=C. |last5=Schulz |first6=W. |last6=Francke  |lastauthoramp=yes |year=2003 |title=Do social parasitic bumblebees use chemical weapons? (Hymenoptera, Apidae) |journal=Journal of Comparative Physiology A |volume=189 |issue=10 |pages=769–775 |doi=10.1007/s00359-003-0451-x |pmid=12955437}}</ref> Usually, cuckoo bumblebees can be described as queen-intolerant [[inquiline]]s, since the host queen is often killed to enable the parasite to produce more offspring,<ref name=Erler/> though some species, such as ''[[Bombus bohemicus|B. bohemicus]]'', actually enjoy increased success when they leave the host queen alive.<ref name=Fisher2>{{cite journal|last=Fisher|first=R.M.|title=Observations on the Behaviors of Three European Cuckoo Bumble Bee Species (Psithyrus)|journal=Insectes Sociaux|date=December 1988|volume=35|issue=4|pages=341–354|doi=10.1007/BF02225810}}</ref>

The female ''Psithyrus'' has a number of morphological adaptations for combat, such as larger mandibles, a tough cuticle and a larger venom sac that increase her chances of taking over a nest.<ref name= Fisher>{{cite journal |author1=Fisher, R. M. |author2=Sampson, B. J. |year=1992 |title=Morphological specializations of the bumble bee social parasite ''Psithyrus ashtoni'' (Cresson) (Hymenoptera, Apidae) |journal=Canadian Entomologist |volume=124 |issue=1 |pages=69–77 |doi=10.4039/Ent12469-1}}</ref> Upon emerging from their cocoons, the ''Psithyrus'' males and females disperse and mate. The males do not survive the winter but, like nonparasitic bumblebee queens, ''Psithyrus'' females find suitable locations to spend the winter and enter diapause after mating. They usually emerge from [[hibernation]] later than their host species. Each species of cuckoo bee has a specific host species, which it may physically resemble.<ref>Macdonald, 2003. p. 12</ref> In the case of the parasitism of ''B. terrestris'' by ''[[Vestal cuckoo bumblebee|B. (Psithyrus) vestalis]]'', genetic analysis of individuals captured in the wild showed that about 42% of the host species' nests at a single location{{efn|The study location was the Botanical Garden Halle (Saale) in Germany, described as a flower-rich region with high and stable abundance of both host and cuckoo species. 24 ''B. terrestris'' workers and 24 drones were captured on foraging flights. 24 male ''B. vestalis'' were similarly captured. DNA analysis was used to estimate how many colonies these individuals came from.<ref name=Erler/>}} had "[lost] their fight against their parasite".<ref name=Erler/>

===Sting===
Queen and worker bumblebees can [[bee sting|sting]]. Unlike in honeybees, a bumblebee's sting lacks barbs, so the bee can sting repeatedly without injuring itself; by the same token, the sting is not left in the wound.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.straightdope.com/mailbag/mbeesting.htm |title=Do bumblebees sting? Once or many times? |accessdate=9 July 2007 |publisher=Straight Dope |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071230082748/http://www.straightdope.com/mailbag/mbeesting.htm |archivedate = 30 December 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://beespotter.mste.illinois.edu/topics/stings/ |title=Bee Stings, BeeSpotter, University of Illinois |publisher=Beespotter.mste.illinois.edu |accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref> Bumblebee species are not normally aggressive, but may sting in defence of their nest, or if harmed. Female cuckoo bumblebees aggressively attack host colony members, and sting the host queen, but ignore other animals unless disturbed.<ref>Goulson, 2013. pp. 118–121</ref>

==Predators, parasites and pathogens==
[[File:Catastrophe for the bumblebees - geograph.org.uk - 899562.jpg|thumb|left|Bumblebee nest dug up and destroyed by a predator, probably a [[badger]]]]
Bumblebees, despite their ability to sting, are eaten by certain predators. Nests may be dug up by [[badger]]s and eaten whole, including any adults present.<ref>Goulson, 2013. p. 132</ref> Adults are preyed upon by robber flies and [[Beewolf|beewolves]] in North America.<ref>Goulson, 2013. p. 126</ref> In Europe, birds including [[bee-eater]]s and [[shrike]]s capture adult bumblebees on the wing; smaller birds such as [[great tit]]s also occasionally learn to take bumblebees, while [[camouflage]]d [[crab spider]]s catch them as they visit flowers.<ref>Goulson, 2013. pp. 126–129</ref>

[[File:Lanius.excubitor5.-.lindsey.jpg|thumb|upright=0.6|Bumblebee stored as food by a [[great grey shrike]]]]
The [[great grey shrike]] is able to detect flying bumblebees up to 100 metres away; once captured, the sting is removed by repeatedly squeezing the insect with the mandibles and wiping the abdomen on a branch.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Cramp |first1=Stanley |title=Handbook of the Birds of Europe, the Middle East and North Africa. Volume VII: Flycatchers to Shrikes |date=1993 |publisher=RSPB / Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |isbn=978-0-198-57510-8 |page=505|display-authors=etal}}</ref> The [[European honey buzzard]] follows flying bees back to their nest, digs out the nest with its feet, and eats larvae, pupae and adults as it finds them.<ref>{{cite web|title=Honey Buzzard: Feeding|url=http://www.rspb.org.uk/discoverandenjoynature/discoverandlearn/birdguide/name/h/honeybuzzard/feeding.aspx|publisher=Royal Society for the Protection of Birds|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref>

Bumblebees are parasitised by tracheal mites, ''[[Locustacarus buchneri]]''; [[protozoa]]ns including ''[[Crithidia|Crithidia bombi]]'' and ''[[Apicystis bombi]]''; and [[microsporidia]]ns including ''[[Nosema bombi]]'' and ''[[Nosema ceranae]]''. The tree bumblebee ''[[Bombus hypnorum|B. hypnorum]]'' has spread into the [[United Kingdom]] despite hosting high levels of a [[nematode]] that normally interferes with queen bees' attempts to establish colonies.<ref>"[http://bumblebeeconservation.org/news/parasites-fail-to-halt-european-bumblebee-invasion-of-the-uk Parasites fail to halt European bumblebee invasion of the UK] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310133729/http://bumblebeeconservation.org/news/parasites-fail-to-halt-european-bumblebee-invasion-of-the-uk |date=10 March 2016 }}", Bumblebee Conservation Trust (retrieved 6 February 2015)</ref> [[Deformed wing virus]] has been found to affect 11% of bumblebees in Great Britain.<ref>"[http://bumblebeeconservation.org/news/new-study-shows-how-bumblebees-can-be-infected-by-honeybee-diseases New study shows how bumblebees can be infected by honeybee diseases] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304040846/http://bumblebeeconservation.org/news/new-study-shows-how-bumblebees-can-be-infected-by-honeybee-diseases |date=4 March 2016 }}", Bumblebee Conservation Trust (retrieved 6 February 2015)</ref>

Female Bee Moths ''([[Aphomia sociella]])'' prefer to lay their eggs in bumblebee nests. The A. sociella larvae will then feed on the eggs, larvae, and pupae left unprotected by the bumble bees, sometimes destroying large parts of the nest.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gambino|first=Parker|date=1995|title=Dolichovespula (Hymenoptera: Vespidae), Hosts of Aphomia sociella (L.) (Lepidoptera: Pyralidae)|journal=Journal of the New York Entomological Society|volume=103|issue=2|pages=165–169|doi=10.2307/25010152|jstor=25010152|doi-broken-date=2018-11-16}}</ref>

==Relationship to humans==
[[File:2005. Марка России stamp hi12612325014b2ce1752cdd2.jpg|thumb|left|Bumblebees and human culture: ''Bombus anachoreta'' on a Russian postage stamp, 2005]]

===Agricultural use===
{{further|List of crop plants pollinated by bees}}

Bumblebees are important [[pollinator]]s of both [[crop]]s and [[wildflower]]s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Modelling bee pollination: enter the 'flight arena' |url=http://www.foodsecurity.ac.uk/research/current/modelling-bee-pollination.html |website=Global Food Security |publisher=Biotechnology and Biological Sciences Research Council |accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref> Because bumblebees do not overwinter the entire colony, they do not stockpile honey, and therefore are not useful as honey producers. Bumblebees are increasingly cultured for agricultural use as pollinators, among other reasons because they can pollinate plants such as [[tomato]] in [[greenhouse]]s by buzz pollination whereas other pollinators cannot.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nrdc.org/OnEarth/06sum/bees3.asp |title=NRDC: OnEarth Magazine, Summer 2006 – The Vanishing |accessdate=9 July 2007}}</ref> Commercial production began in 1987, when Roland De Jonghe founded the Biobest company; in 1988 they produced enough nests to pollinate 40 hectares of [[tomato]]es. The industry grew quickly, starting with other companies in the Netherlands. Bumblebee nests, mainly of buff-tailed bumblebees, are produced in at least 30 factories around the world; over a million nests are grown annually in Europe; Turkey is a major producer.<ref>Goulson, 2013. pp. 169–170</ref>

Bumblebees are [[Northern Hemisphere]] animals. When [[red clover]] was introduced as a crop to [[New Zealand]] in the nineteenth century, it was found to have no local pollinators, and clover seed had accordingly to be imported each year. Four species of bumblebee from the United Kingdom were therefore imported as pollinators. In 1885 and 1886 the Canterbury Acclimatization Society brought in 442 queens, of which 93 survived and quickly multiplied. As planned, red clover was soon being produced from locally-grown seed.<ref name="Macdonald, 2003. p. 6"/> Bumblebees are also reared commercially to pollinate tomatoes grown in [[greenhouse]]s.<ref name="NZ-bees"/> The New Zealand population of [[buff-tailed bumblebee]]s naturally colonised [[Tasmania]], 1,500 miles away, in 1992.<ref>Goulson, 2013. pp. 69–70</ref>

Some concerns exist about the impact of the international trade in mass-produced bumblebee colonies. Evidence from Japan<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/s10841-007-9071-z |title=Displacement of Japanese native bumblebees by the recently introduced Bombus terrestris (L.) (Hymenoptera: Apidae) |year=2007 |last1=Inoue |first1=Maki N. |last2=Yokoyama |first2=Jun |last3=Washitani |first3=Izumi |journal=Journal of Insect Conservation |volume=12 |issue=2 |pages=135–146}}</ref> and South America<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1007/s11829-013-9264-1 |title=Assessing the impact of the invasive buff-tailed bumblebee (Bombus terrestris) on the pollination of the native Chilean herb Mimulus luteus |year=2013 |last1=Esterio |first1=Gabriel |last2=Cares-Suárez |first2=Roxana |last3=González-Browne|first3=Catalina |last4=Salinas |first4=Patricia |last5=Carvallo|first5=Gastón |last6=Medel |first6=Rodrigo |journal=Arthropod-Plant Interactions|volume=7 |issue=4 |pages=467–474}}</ref> indicates  bumblebees can escape and naturalise in new environments, causing damage to native pollinators. Greater use of native pollinators, such as ''[[Bombus ignitus]]'' in China and Japan, has occurred as a result.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Genetic Structure of Asian Populations of Bombus ignitus (Hymenoptera: Apidae)|url = http://jhered.oxfordjournals.org/content/95/1/46|journal = Journal of Heredity|date = January 2004|issn = 0022-1503|pmid = 14757729|pages = 46–52|volume = 95|issue = 1|doi = 10.1093/jhered/esh008|first = Z.-Y.|last = Shao|first2 = H.-X.|last2 = Mao|first3 = W.-J.|last3 = Fu|first4 = M.|last4 = Ono|first5 = D.-S.|last5 = Wang|first6 = M.|last6 = Bonizzoni|first7 = Y.-P.|last7 = Zhang}}</ref> In addition, mounting evidence indicates mass-produced bumblebees may also carry diseases, harmful to wild bumblebees<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2005.11.013 |title=Plight of the bumble bee: Pathogen spillover from commercial to wild populations |year=2006 |last1=Colla |first1=Sheila R.|last2=Otterstatter |first2=Michael C.|last3=Gegear|first3=Robert J. |last4=Thomson |first4=James D. |journal=Biological Conservation |volume=129|issue=4|pages=461–467}}</ref><ref name="Graystock2013">{{cite journal|doi=10.1111/1365-2664.12134 |layurl=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-23347867 |laysource=BBC News |laydate=18 July 2013 |title=The Trojan hives: Pollinator pathogens, imported and distributed in bumblebee colonies |year=2013 |last1=Graystock |first1=Peter|last2=Yates |first2=Kathryn|last3=Evison |first3=Sophie E. F. |last4=Darvill |first4=Ben |last5=Goulson |first5=Dave |last6=Hughes |first6=William O. H. |editor1-last=Osborne |editor1-first=Juliet |journal=Journal of Applied Ecology |pages=n/a}}</ref> and honeybees.<ref name="Graystock2013" />

In Canada and Sweden it has been shown that growing a mosaic of different crops encourages bumblebees and provides higher yields than does a monoculture of oilseed rape, despite the fact that the bees were attracted to the crop.<ref name="Goulson, 2013. pp. 169–172">Goulson, 2013. pp. 169–172</ref>

===Population decline===
<!--this is very close to a COATRACK, should maybe become a separate article-->

Bumblebee species are declining in Europe, North America, and Asia due to a number of factors, including land-use change that reduces their food plants. In North America, pathogens are possibly having a stronger negative effect especially for the subgenus<!--source says ''sensu stricto'', "in the narrow sense"--> ''Bombus''.<ref>{{Cite journal |year=2009 |journal=Apidologie |volume=40 |issue=3 |pages=367–387 |url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/research-curation/research/projects/bombus/Williams&Osborne09_review.pdf| doi=10.1051/apido/2009025 |title=Bumblebee vulnerability and conservation world-wide |first1=Paul H. |last1=Williams |first2=Juliet L. |last2=Osborne}}</ref> A major impact on bumblebees was caused by the mechanisation of agriculture, accelerated by the urgent need to increase food production during the Second World War. Small farms depended on horses to pull implements and carts. The horses were fed on clover and hay, both of which were permanently grown on a typical farm. Little artificial fertiliser was used. Farms thus provided flowering clover and flower-rich meadows, favouring bumblebees. Mechanisation removed the need for horses and most of the clover; artificial fertilisers encouraged the growth of taller grasses, outcompeting the meadow flowers. Most of the flowers, and the bumblebees that fed on them, disappeared from Britain by the early 1980s. The last native British short-haired bumblebee was captured near [[Dungeness (headland)|Dungeness]] in 1988.<ref>Goulson, 2013. pp. 4–6</ref> This significant increase in pesticide and fertilizer use associated with the industrialization of agriculture has had adverse effects on the genus ''Bombus''. The bees are directly exposed to the chemicals in two ways: by consuming nectar that has been directly treated with pesticide, or through physical contact with treated plants and flowers. The species ''[[Bombus hortorum]]'' in particular has been found to be impacted by the pesticides; their brood development has been reduced and their memory has been negatively affected. Additionally, pesticide use negatively impacts colony development and size.<ref>{{Cite journal|url = |title = A Newly Recorded Neogregarine (Protozoa, Apicomplexa), Parasite in Honey Bees (Apis Mellifera) and Bumble Bees (Bombus Spp)|last = Lipa|first = JJ|date = 1992|journal = Adipologie|doi = 10.1051/apido:19920605|pmid = |access-date = |last2 = Triggiani|first2 = O.|issue = 6|volume = 23|pages = 533–536}}</ref>

Bumblebees are in danger in many developed countries due to [[habitat destruction]] and collateral [[pesticide]] damage. The [[European Food Safety Authority]] ruled that three [[neonicotinoid]] pesticides ([[clothianidin]], [[imidacloprid]], and [[thiamethoxam]]) presented [[Imidacloprid effects on bee population|a high risk for bees]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Pesticides : un risque enfin admis pour les abeilles |url=http://www.lemonde.fr/planete/article/2013/01/16/pesticides-un-risque-enfin-admis-pour-les-abeilles_1817630_3244.html |newspaper=Le Monde |accessdate=23 December 2013 |date=16 January 2013 |first=Stéphane |last= Foucart}}</ref> While most work on neonicotinoid toxicity has looked at honeybees, a study on ''B. terrestris'' showed that "field-realistic" levels of imidacloprid significantly reduced growth rate and cut production of new queens by 85%, implying a "considerable negative effect" on wild bumblebee populations throughout the developed world.<ref name=Whitehorn>{{cite journal |last1=Whitehorn |first1=Penelope R.|last2=O'Connor |first2=Stephanie |last3=Wackers |first3=Felix L. |last4=Goulson |first4=Dave |title=Neonicotinoid Pesticide Reduces Bumble Bee Colony Growth and Queen Production |journal=Science |date=20 April 2012 |volume=336 |issue=6079 |pages=351–352 |doi=10.1126/science.1215025 |url=http://www.sciencemag.org/content/336/6079/351|bibcode = 2012Sci...336..351W |pmid=22461500}}</ref>
However, in another study, following chronic exposure to field-realistic levels of the neonicotinoid pesticide thiamethoxam, colony weight gain was not affected, nor were the number or mass of sexuals produced.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Stanley|first1=Dara A.|last2=Raine|first2=Nigel E.|title=Bumblebee colony development following chronic exposure to field-realistic levels of the neonicotinoid pesticide thiamethoxam under laboratory conditions|journal=Scientific Reports|date=2017|page=8005|doi=10.1038/s41598-017-08752-x|pmid=28808317|pmc=5556064|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-017-08752-x|volume=7|issue=1}}</ref> Low levels of neonicotinoids can reduce the number of bumblebees in a colony by as much as 55%, and cause dysfunction in the bumblebees' brains. The Bumblebee Conservation Trust considers this evidence of reduced brain function "particularly alarming given that bumblebees rely upon their intelligence to go about their daily tasks."<ref>{{cite web|title=Bumblebee brains affected by neonicotinoids|url=http://bumblebeeconservation.org/news/bumblebee-brains-affected-by-neonicotinoids|publisher=Bumblebee Conservation Trust|accessdate=19 February 2015|date=3 February 2014|quote=New research has emerged from the Universities of Dundee and St. Andrews which shows that accepted environmental levels of neonicotinoids impair bumblebee brain functionality and consequently negatively impact the performance of whole colonies.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150219162725/http://bumblebeeconservation.org/news/bumblebee-brains-affected-by-neonicotinoids|archive-date=19 February 2015|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}} Research was published in the Journal of the Federation of American Societies for Experimental Biology by Chris Connolly and others.</ref> A study on ''B. terrestris'' had results that suggests that use of neonicotinoid pesticides can affect how well bumblebees are able to forage and pollinate. Bee colonies that had been affected by the pesticide released more foragers and collected more pollen than bees who had not been dosed with neonicotinoid.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stanley|first=Dara|date=14 March 2016|title=Chronic exposure to a neonicotinoid pesticide alters the interactions between bumblebees and wild plants|journal=Functional Ecology|doi=10.1111/1365-2435.12644|pmid=27512241|pmc=4950133|volume=30|issue=7|pages=1132–1139}}</ref> Although the bees affected by the pesticide were able to collect more pollen, they took a longer amount of time doing so.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/2890308/pesticides-damage-bumblebees-pollinating-skills-and-that-spells-trouble-for-our-food/|title=Pesticides Damage Bumblebees' Pollinating Skills — And That Spells Trouble For Our Food|last=Hazen|first=Shelley|date=15 March 2016|website=Inquistr|publisher=|access-date=30 March 2016}}</ref>

Of 19 species of native nestmaking bumblebees and six species of cuckoo bumblebees formerly widespread in [[United Kingdom|Britain]],<ref>{{Cite book |chapter-url=http://drkaae.com/content/chapter-18-bees-wasps-and-ants |first=Richard |last=Kaae |chapter=Bees, Wasps and Ants |date=nd |title=Insect & Civilization Part 2 |accessdate=23 December 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224121927/http://drkaae.com/content/chapter-18-bees-wasps-and-ants |archivedate=24 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> three have been extirpated,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2006/07/060728162546.htm |title=Scientists map the flight of the bumblebee |publisher=Science Daily |date=28 July 2006 |author=University of Newcastle-upon-Tyne |authorlink=Newcastle University}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Harman, Alan |title=Bumblebee Shortage |journal=Bee Culture |volume=59 |date=July 2003}}</ref> eight are in [[pollinator decline|serious decline]], and only six remain widespread.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/research-curation/projects/bombus/decline.html |author=Williams, Paul H. |year=1986 |title=Environmental change and the distributions of British bumble bees (''Bombus'' Latr.) |journal=Bee World |volume=67 |issue=2 |pages=50–61 |doi=10.1080/0005772x.1986.11098871}}</ref> Similar declines have been reported in [[Ireland]], with four species designated [[Endangered species|endangered]], and another two considered [[Vulnerable species|vulnerable]] to extinction.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fitzpatrick |first1=U. |first2=T. E. |last2=Murray |first3=A. |last3=Byrne |first4=R. J. |last4=Paxton  |first5=M. J. F. |last5=Brown |year=2006 |url=http://www.npws.ie/en/media/NPWS/Publications/Redlists/Media,4860,en.pdf |title=Regional red list of Irish Bees |publisher=Report to National Parks and Wildlife Service (Ireland) and Environment and Heritage Service (N. Ireland)}}{{dead link|date=June 2014}}</ref> A decline in bumblebee numbers could cause large-scale changes to the countryside, resulting from inadequate pollination of certain plants.<ref name=VaneFarm>{{cite journal |year=2008 |title=World's first bumblebee sanctuary creates a buzz |journal=Geographical |volume=80 |issue=10 |page=8 | url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_hb3120/is_10_80/ai_n30892916/}}</ref>

Some bumblebees native to North America are also vanishing, such as ''[[Bombus balteatus]]'',<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Miller-Struttmann|first=Nicole E.|last2=Geib|first2=Jennifer C.|last3=Franklin|first3=James D.|last4=Kevan|first4=Peter G.|last5=Holdo|first5=Ricardo M.|last6=Ebert-May|first6=Diane|last7=Lynn|first7=Austin M.|last8=Kettenbach|first8=Jessica A.|last9=Hedrick|first9=Elizabeth|date=2015-09-25|title=Functional mismatch in a bumble bee pollination mutualism under climate change|url=http://science.sciencemag.org/content/349/6255/1541|journal=Science|language=en|volume=349|issue=6255|pages=1541–1544|doi=10.1126/science.aab0868|issn=0036-8075|pmid=26404836|bibcode=2015Sci...349.1541M}}</ref> ''[[Bombus terricola]]'',<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wong |first1=Lisa |last2=Cameron |first2=Sydney |last3=Favret |first3=Colin |last4=Jennifer |first4=Grixti |title=Decline of bumble bees (''Bombus'') in the North American Midwest|journal=Biological Conservation |date=2009 |volume=142 |pages=75–84 |doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2008.09.027}}</ref> ''[[Bombus affinis]]'',<ref name="abcnews">{{cite news|last1=Flesher|first1=Lohn|title=Rusty Patched Bumblebee Declared Endangered|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/apnewsbreak-rusty-patched-bumblebee-declared-endangered-44677209|accessdate=10 January 2017|agency=APNews|publisher=ABC News|date=10 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Fact Sheet Rusty Patched Bumble Bee (Bombus affinis)|url=https://www.fws.gov/midwest/endangered/insects/rpbb/factsheetrpbb.html|website=Endangered Species|publisher=U.S. Fish & Wildlife Service|accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref> and ''[[Bombus occidentalis]]'', and one, ''[[Bombus franklini]]'', may be extinct.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.xerces.org/bumblebees/ |title=Bumble Bee Conservation |publisher=The Xerces Society for Invertebrate Conservation |accessdate=20 June 2010}}</ref> In South America, ''Bombus bellicosus'' was [[Local extinction|extirpate]]d in the northern limit of its distribution range, probably due to intense land use and climate change effects.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Martins |first1=Aline C. |last2=Melo |first2=Gabriel A. R. |title=Has the bumblebee Bombus bellicosus gone extinct in the northern portion of its distribution range in Brazil? |journal=Journal of Insect Conservation |date=2009 |volume=14 |issue=2 |pages=207–210 |doi=10.1007/s10841-009-9237-y}}</ref>

===Conservation efforts===
[[File:Vallhumla Hane06178.jpg|thumb|left|Drone short-haired bumblebee, ''[[Bombus subterraneus]]''. The species was successfully reintroduced to England from Sweden.]]

In 2006 the bumblebee researcher [[Dave Goulson]] founded a registered charity, the [[Bumblebee Conservation Trust]], to prevent the extinction "of any of the UK's bumblebees."<ref>{{cite web | url=http://bumblebeeconservation.org/about-us/ | title=About us | publisher=Bumblebee Conservation Trust | accessdate=10 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=Guardian>{{cite news |last1=Barkham |first1=Patrick |title=A Sting in the Tale by Dave Goulson – review |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/may/18/sting-tale-dave-goulson-review |accessdate=26 June 2014|work=The Guardian |issue=18 May 2013}}</ref> In 2009 and 2010, the Trust attempted to reintroduce the short-haired bumblebee, ''[[Bombus subterraneus]]'', which had become extinct in Britain, from the British-derived populations surviving in New Zealand from their introduction there a century earlier.<ref>Goulson, 2013. pp. 1–14, 227–241</ref> From 2011 the Trust, in partnership with [[Natural England]], Hymettus and the [[Royal Society for the Protection of Birds|RSPB]], has reintroduced short-haired bumblebee queens from [[Skåne]] in southern Sweden to restored flower-rich meadows at Dungeness in Kent. The queens were checked for [[mites]] and [[American foulbrood]] disease. Agri-environment schemes spread across the neighbouring area of [[Romney Marsh]] have been set up to provide over 800 hectares of additional flower-rich habitat for the bees. By the summer of 2013, workers of the species were found near the release zone, proving that nests had been established. The restored habitat has produced a revival in at least five "Schedule 41 priority" species: the ruderal bumblebee, ''[[Bombus ruderatus]]'';  the red-shanked carder bee, ''[[Bombus ruderarius]]''; the shrill carder bee, ''[[Bombus sylvarum]]''; the brown-banded carder bee, ''[[Bombus humilis]]'' and the moss carder bee,  ''[[Bombus muscorum]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Short-haired bumblebee reintroduction |url=http://bumblebeeconservation.org/about-us/case-study/short-haired-bumblebee-reintroduction/ |publisher=Bumblebee Conservation Trust |accessdate=19 February 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216002921/http://bumblebeeconservation.org/about-us/case-study/short-haired-bumblebee-reintroduction/ |archivedate=16 February 2015 }}</ref>

The world's first bumblebee sanctuary was established at Vane Farm in the [[Loch Leven (Kinross)|Loch Leven National Nature Reserve]] in Scotland in 2008.<ref name=VaneFarm/> In 2011, London's [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]] led the establishment of an [[International Union for the Conservation of Nature]] Bumblebee Specialist Group, chaired by Dr. Paul H. Williams,<ref name=NHM_BSG>{{Cite journal |url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/research-curation/life-sciences/terrestrial-invertebrates/research/hymenoptera-research/bumble-bee-research/bumblebee-specialist-group/index.html |title=Bumblebee Specialist Group |accessdate=23 December 2013 |publisher=Natural History Museum|location=London, UK}}</ref> to assess the threat status of bumblebee species worldwide using [[Red List]] criteria.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://cmsdata.iucn.org/downloads/bumblebee_sg_proofed.pdf |title=2011 Update |publisher=IUCN |accessdate=7 October 2012}}</ref>

Bumblebee conservation is in its infancy in many parts of the world, but with the realization of the important part they play in pollination of crops, efforts are being made to manage farmland better. Enhancing the wild bee population can be done by the planting of wildflower strips, and in New Zealand, bee nesting boxes have achieved some success, perhaps because there are few burrowing mammals to provide potential nesting sites in that country.<ref name="Goulson, 2013. pp. 169–172"/>

===Misconception about flight===
{{anchor|Flight}}
[[File:AD2009Aug08 Bombus pratorum.jpg|thumb|right|A widely believed falsehood holds that scientists proved bumblebees to be incapable of flight.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sciencenews.org/view/generic/id/5400/title/Math_Trek__Flight_of_the_Bumblebee|title=Flight of the Bumblebee |author=Ivars Peterson |date=11 September 2004 |work=[[Science News]] |accessdate=29 May 2012}} "the venerable line about scientists having proved that a bumblebee can't fly appears regularly in magazine and newspaper stories. It's also the kind of item that can come up in a cocktail party conversation when the subject turns to science or technology. [...] Often, the statement is made in a distinctly disparaging tone aimed at putting down those know-it-all scientists and engineers who are so smart yet can't manage to understand something that's apparent to everyone else. [...] the story has had remarkable staying power, and the myth persists that science says a bumblebee can't fly. Indeed, this myth has taken on a new life of its own as a piece of "[[urban legend|urban folklore]]" on the Internet."</ref>|alt=A bumblebee landing on a purple flower]]
{{further|Insect flight}}

According to 20th-century [[folklore]], the laws of [[aerodynamics]] prove the bumblebee should be incapable of [[flight]], as it does not have the capacity (in terms of wing size or beats per second) to achieve flight with the degree of [[wing loading]] necessary.<ref name=Physics/>

{{quote|'Supposedly someone did a back of the envelope calculation, taking the weight of a bumblebee and its wing area into account, and worked out that if it only flies at a couple of metres per second, the wings wouldn't produce enough lift to hold the bee up,' explains Charlie Ellington, Professor of Animal Mechanics at Cambridge University.<ref name=Physics>{{cite web |url=http://www.physics.org/featuredetail.asp?id=32 |title=The secrets of bee flight |accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref>}}

The origin of this claim has been difficult to pin down with any certainty. [[John H. McMasters]] recounted an anecdote about an unnamed Swiss aerodynamicist at a dinner party who performed some rough calculations and concluded, presumably in jest, that according to the equations, bumblebees cannot fly.<ref>{{cite journal |author=McMasters, John H. |title=The flight of the bumblebee and related myths of entomological engineering |journal=American Scientist |volume=77 |issue=2 |date=March–April 1989 |pages=146–169 |bibcode=1989AmSci..77..164M}} cited in {{cite book |author=Jay Ingram |title=The Barmaid's Brain |publisher=[[Aurum Press]] |year=2001 |pages=91–92 |isbn=978-1-85410-633-9}}</ref> In later years, McMasters backed away from this origin, suggesting there could be multiple sources, and the earliest he has found was a reference in the 1934 book ''{{lang|fr|Le Vol des Insectes}}'' by French entomologist [[Antoine Magnan]] (1881–1938); they had applied the equations of [[drag (physics)|air resistance]] to insects and found  their flight was impossible, but  "One shouldn't be surprised that the results of the calculations don't square with reality".<ref>{{cite book |author=Jay Ingram |title=The Barmaid's Brain |publisher=[[Aurum Press]] |year=2001 |pages=91–92 |isbn=978-1-85410-633-9}}</ref>

The following passage appears in the introduction to ''Le Vol des Insectes'':<ref name=Magnan>{{cite book |last1=Magnan |first1=Antoine |title=Le Vol des Insectes |date=1934 |publisher=Hermann |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Le_vol_des_insectes.html?id=RoXgOgAACAAJ}}</ref>

{{quote|''{{lang|fr|Tout d'abord poussé par ce qui se fait en aviation, j'ai appliqué aux insectes les lois de la résistance de l'air, et je suis arrivé avec M. Sainte-Laguë à cette conclusion que leur vol est impossible.}}''}}

This translates to:

{{quote|''First prompted by what is done in aviation, I applied the laws of air resistance to insects, and I arrived, with Mr. Sainte-Laguë, at this conclusion that their flight is impossible.''}}

Magnan refers to his assistant [[André Sainte-Laguë]].<ref>"The bumblebee story can be traced back to a 1934 book by entomologist Antoine Magnan, who refers to a calculation by his assistant André Sainte-Laguë, who was an engineer. The conclusion was presumably based on the fact that the maximum possible lift produced by aircraft wings as small as a bumblebee's wings and traveling as slowly as a bee in flight would be much less than the weight of a bee."{{Cite journal
 | pmid = 11396342
| year = 2001
| author1 = Dickinson
| first1 = M
| title = Solving the mystery of insect flight
| journal = Scientific American
| volume = 284
| issue = 6
| pages = 48–57
 | doi=10.1038/scientificamerican0601-48
| bibcode = 2001SciAm.284f..48D
}}</ref> Some credit physicist [[Ludwig Prandtl]] (1875–1953) of the [[University of Göttingen]] in Germany with popularizing the idea. Others say Swiss gas dynamicist [[Jacob Ackeret]] (1898–1981) did the calculations.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Snopes |title=Bumblebees Can't Fly |url=http://www.snopes.com/science/bumblebees.asp |accessdate=9 April 2013}}</ref>

[[File:Bumble Bee in flight.JPG|thumb|left|Bumblebee in flight. It has its tongue extended and a laden pollen basket.]]

The calculations that purported to show that bumblebees cannot fly are based upon a simplified linear treatment of [[oscillating]] [[airfoil|aerofoils]]. The method assumes small amplitude oscillations without flow separation. This ignores the effect of [[Stall (flight)#Dynamic stall|dynamic stall]] (an airflow separation inducing a large [[vortex]] above the wing), which briefly produces several times the lift of the aerofoil in regular flight. More sophisticated aerodynamic analysis shows the bumblebee can fly because its wings encounter dynamic stall in every [[oscillation|oscillation cycle]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Bumblebees finally cleared for takeoff |url=http://www.news.cornell.edu/releases/March00/APS_Wang.hrs.html |publisher=Cornell Chronicle |date=20 March 2000 |accessdate=26 January 2008}}</ref>

Additionally, [[John Maynard Smith]], a noted biologist with a strong background in aeronautics, has pointed out that bumblebees would not be expected to sustain flight, as they would need to generate too much power given their tiny wing area. However, in aerodynamics experiments with other insects, he found that [[viscosity]] at the scale of small insects meant even their small wings can move a very large volume of air relative to their size, and this reduces the power required to sustain flight by an order of magnitude.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vega.org.uk/video/programme/84 |title=Flight in Birds and Aeroplanes – Science Video |author=[[John Maynard Smith]] |accessdate=20 June 2010}}</ref>

===In music and literature===
{{listen|filename=Rimsky-Korsakov - flight of the bumblebee.oga|title=Flight of the Bumblebee|description=''Flight of the Bumblebee'' performed by the US Army Band|format=[[Ogg]]}}
[[File:Rimsky-Korsakov Elson 1915.png|thumb|left|upright|The Russian composer [[Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov]] wrote the ''[[Flight of the Bumblebee]]'', c. 1900]]
The orchestral interlude ''[[Flight of the Bumblebee]]'' was composed (c. 1900) by [[Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov]]. It represents the turning of Prince Guidon into a bumblebee so he can fly away to visit his father, Tsar Saltan, in the opera ''[[The Tale of Tsar Saltan]]'',<ref>{{cite book |title=A history of Russian music: from Kamarinskaya to Babi Yar |last=Maes |first=Francis |year=2002 |publisher= University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-21815-4 |page=191 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=SqWcR336iW0C |accessdate=3 April 2010}}</ref> although the music may reflect the flight of a [[Calliphoridae|bluebottle]] rather than a bumblebee.<ref>{{cite book |title=The science of music |author=Maconie, Robin |year=1997 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=978-0-19-816648-1 |page=184 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=i7-xLzn2ZS8C |accessdate=3 April 2010}}</ref> The music inspired [[Walt Disney]] to feature a bumblebee in his 1940 animated musical ''[[Fantasia (1940 film)|Fantasia]]'' and have it sound as if it were flying in all parts of the theater. This early attempt at "[[surround sound]]" was unsuccessful, and the music was excluded from the film's release.<ref>{{cite book |title=Surround sound: up and running |author=Holman, Tomlinson |year=2007 |publisher=Focal Press |isbn=978-0-240-80829-1 |pages=3–4 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=nnLAD1N_MNIC |accessdate=3 April 2010}}</ref>

In 1599, during the reign of [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth I]], someone, possibly Tailboys Dymoke, published ''Caltha Poetarum: Or The Bumble Bee'', under the pseudonym "T. Cutwode".<ref>{{cite web |title=Caltha poetarum: or The bumble bee. Composed by T. Cutvvode Esquyre. |url=http://quod.lib.umich.edu/e/eebo/A19732.0001.001?view=toc |publisher=University of Michigan Libraries |accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref> This was one of nine books [[censorship|censored]] under the [[Bishops' Ban of 1599|Bishop's Ban]] issued by the Archbishop of Canterbury [[John Whitgift]] and the Bishop of London [[Richard Bancroft]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Caltha Poetarum |url=http://www.banned-books.info/book-content.php?key=220 |website=Banned Books |accessdate=11 February 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150211180241/http://www.banned-books.info/book-content.php?key=220 |archivedate=11 February 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

[[File:Emily Dickinson daguerreotype.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Emily Dickinson]] wrote a poem about a bumblebee. [[Daguerreotype]], c. 1848]]
[[Emily Dickinson]] made a bumblebee the subject of her parody of [[Isaac Watts]]'s well-known poem about honeybees, ''How Doth the Little Busy Bee'' (1715). Where Watts wrote "How skilfully she builds her cell! How neat she spreads the wax!",<ref>{{cite web|last1=Watts |first1=Isaac |title=How Doth the Little Busy Bee |url=http://www.poets.org/poetsorg/poem/how-doth-little-busy-bee |website=Poets.org| date=1715| accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref> Dickinson's poem, "The Bumble-Bee's Religion" (1881) begins "His little Hearse-like Figure / Unto itself a Dirge / To a delusive Lilac / The vanity divulge / Of Industry and Morals / And every righteous thing / For the divine Perdition / of Idleness and Spring." The letter was said to have enclosed a dead bee.<ref name="Morgan2010">{{cite book |last=Morgan |first=Victoria N. |title=Emily Dickinson and Hymn Culture: Tradition and Experience |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8qE1bCYzkd4C&pg=PA183 |year=2010 |publisher=Ashgate |isbn=978-0-7546-6942-5 |pages=183–184}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Dickinson |first1=Emily |title=The Bumble-Bee's Religion, in a letter to Gilbert Dickinson, 1881 | work=The Letters of Emily Dickinson | page=712 |date=1986 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Vy7VIpug6Q8C&pg=PA701 |publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=9780674526273 }}</ref>

The entomologist [[Otto Plath]] wrote ''Bumblebees and Their Ways'' in 1934.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Steinberg |first1=Peter K. |title=Biography |url=http://www.sylviaplath.info/biography.html |publisher=SylviaPlath.info |accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref> His daughter, the poet [[Sylvia Plath]], wrote a group of poems about bees late in 1962, within four months of her suicide,<ref>{{cite web |title=Sylvia Plath and the Bees |url=http://dublinbees.org/members-area/sylvia-plath-and-the-bees/ |publisher=The County Dublin Beekeepers' Association |accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref> transforming her father's interest into her poetry.<ref name="Kirk2004">{{cite book |last=Kirk |first=Connie Ann |title=Sylvia Plath: A Biography |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NBlJYGHVESwC&pg=PA14 |date=1 January 2004 |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |isbn=978-0-313-33214-2 |page=14}}</ref>

[[File:Moses Harris00.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Bumblebees of different species illustrated by [[Moses Harris]] in his 1782 ''Exposition of English Insects'']]
The scientist and illustrator [[Moses Harris]] (1731–1785) painted accurate watercolour drawings of bumblebees in his ''An Exposition of English Insects Including the Several Classes of Neuroptera, Hymenoptera, & Diptera, or Bees, Flies, & Libellulae (1776–80)''.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Exposition of English insects |url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/exposition-of-english-insects-including-the-several-classes-of-neuroptera-hymenoptera-diptera-or-bees-flies-libellulae-exhibiting-on-51-copper-plates-near-500-figures-accurately-drawn-highly-finished-in-colours-from-nature-the-whole-minutely-described-arranged-named-according-to-the-linnean-system-with-remarks/oclc/15094019 |publisher=WorldCat |accessdate=1 March 2015|year=1782 }}</ref>

Bumblebees appear as characters, often eponymously, in children's books. The surname [[Albus Dumbledore|Dumbledore]] in the [[Harry Potter]] series (1997–2007) is an old name for bumblebee.<ref name=WebsterDumbledor/> [[J. K. Rowling]] said the name "seemed to suit the headmaster, because one of his passions is music and I imagined him walking around humming to himself".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.accio-quote.org/articles/1999/0399-barnesandnoble.html |title=Barnes and Noble interview, 19 March 1999 |date=19 March 1999 |accessdate=28 February 2007 |publisher=AccioQuote! |last=Rowling |first=J. K.}}</ref> [[J. R. R. Tolkien]], in his poem ''[[Errantry]]'', also used the name Dumbledor, but for a large bee-like creature.

Among the many books for younger children are ''Bumble the Bee'' by Yvon Douran and Tony Neal (2014); ''Bertie Bumble Bee'' by K. I. Al-Ghani (2012); ''Ben the Bumble Bee: How do bees make honey?'' by Romessa Awadalla (2015); ''Bumble Bee Bob Has a Big Butt'' by Papa Campbell (2012); ''Buzz, Buzz, Buzz! Went Bumble-bee'' by Colin West (1997); ''Bumble Bee'' by Margaret Wise Brown (2000); ''How the Bumble Came to Bee'' by Paul and Ella Quarry (2012); ''The Adventures of Professor Bumble and the Bumble Bees'' by Stephen Brailovsky (2010). Among [[Beatrix Potter]]'s "little books", Babbity Bumble and other members of her nest appear in ''[[The Tale of Mrs. Tittlemouse]]''<!--overlinks, these seem sensible here--> (1910).

[[Bumblebee (Transformers)|Bumblebee]] is the name of a prominent character in the [[Transformers]] franchise. His name denotes his black-on-yellow vehicle paint job, directly referencing the bee genus because of its black and yellow stripes. ''Bumblebee'' is also the name of an automotive [[racing stripe]] that wraps around the grill instead of down the centre of the vehicle; it can be found mainly on [[Chevrolet Camaro]]s (which happens to be the Transformers Autobot's most popular vehicle mode).

