[[File:Korere 11.jpg|thumbnail|A collection of kōrere in Te Papa, Museum of New Zealand.]]
A '''kōrere''' is a traditional [[Māori culture|Māori]] feeding funnel that was used during facial tattooing to feed men of high status. Men receiving [[tā moko]] whose mouths were swollen would receive mulched or [[puréed]] food through the kōrere.<ref name=TePapaKorere>{{cite web|title=Object: Korere (feeding funnel)|url=http://collections.tepapa.govt.nz/object/147561|publisher=Museum of New Zealand - Te Papa Tongrewa|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>  It was also used to feed [[tohunga]] that were under [[Tapu (Polynesian culture)|tapu]].<ref name=TeAraKorere>{{cite web|title=Traditional Māori religion – ngā karakia a te Māori - Spiritual concepts|url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/object/30793/korere|publisher=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>

