{{Use American English|date=February 2013}}
{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}
{{History of Romania| Antiquity}}
Several theories address the issue of the '''origin of the Romanians'''. The [[Romanian language]] descends from the [[Vulgar Latin]] dialects spoken in the [[Roman provinces]] north of the "[[Jireček Line]]" (a proposed notional line separating the predominantly [[Latin language|Latin-speaking]] territories from the [[Koine Greek|Greek-speaking]] lands in [[Southeastern Europe]]) in [[Late Antiquity]]. The theory of Daco-Roman continuity argues that the [[Romanians]] are mainly descended from the [[Daco-Romans]], a people developing through the cohabitation of the native [[Dacians]] and the Roman colonists in the province of [[Dacia Traiana]] (primarily in present-day [[Romania]]) north of the river [[Danube]]. The competing immigrationist theory states that the Romanians' ethnogenesis commenced in the provinces south of the river with Romanized local populations (known as [[Vlachs]] in the Middle Ages) spreading through mountain refuges, both south to [[Greece]] and north through the [[Carpathian Mountains]].  According to the "admigration theory", migrations from the [[Balkan Peninsula]] to the lands north of the Danube contributed to the survival of a Romance-speaking population in those territories.

Political motivations{{mdash}}the Transylvanian Romanians' efforts to achieve their emancipation, Austro-Hungarian and Romanian{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=278}} expansionism, and Hungarian irredentism{{mdash}}influenced the development of the theories, and "national passions"{{sfn|Hitchins|2014|p=17}} still color the debates. In 2013, authors of ''The Cambridge History of the Romance Languages'' came to the conclusion that the "historical, archaeological and linguistic data available do not seem adequate to give a definitive answer" in the debate.{{sfn|Andreose|Renzi|2013|p=287}} Their view was accepted by scholars contributing to ''The Oxford Guide to the Romance Languages'', published in 2016, which concludes that "the location and extent of the territory where "Daco-Romance" originated" is uncertain.{{sfn|Maiden|2016|p=91}}

==Historic background==
{{Main|History of the Balkans|History of Romania}}

[[File:Balkans 200AD.png|thumb|alt=Roman provinces in Southeastern Europe|[[Roman province]]s (dark blue) in [[Southeastern Europe]], ''c.'' 200&nbsp;AD. Romanian descended from a variant of Vulgar Latin spoken in one or more Latin-speaking provinces.]]

Three major ethnic groups{{spaced ndash}}the [[Dacians]], [[Illyrians]] and [[Thracians]]{{spaced ndash}}inhabited the northern regions of Southeastern Europe in Antiquity.{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=9}} Modern knowledge of their languages is based on limited evidence (primarily on proper names), making all scholarly theories proposing a strong relationship between the three languages or between Thracian and Dacian speculative.{{sfn|Fortson|2004|p=405}} The Illyrians were the first to be conquered by the Romans, who organized their territory into the province of [[Illyricum (Roman province)|Illyricum]] around 60 BC.{{sfn|Wilkes|1992|p=208}} In the lands inhabited by Thracians, the Romans set up the province of [[Moesia]] in 6&nbsp;AD, and [[Thracia]] forty years later.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=110}} Present-day [[Dobruja]] was attached to Moesia in 46.{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=4}} The Romans annihilated the [[Dacian kingdom]] to the north of the [[Lower Danube]] under Emperor [[Trajan]] in 106.{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=5}} Its western territories were organized into the [[Roman Dacia|province of Dacia]] (or "Dacia Traiana"), but [[Maramureș]] and further regions inhabited by the [[Costoboci]], [[Bastarnae]] and other tribes remained free of Roman rule.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=98}} The Romans officially abandoned Dacia under Emperor [[Aurelian]] (''r.'' 270&ndash;275), who organized a new province bearing the same name ("[[Dacia Aureliana]]") south of the Lower Danube.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|pp=103-104}} Although Roman forts were erected north of the Danube in the 320s,{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=116}} the river became the boundary between the empire and the [[Goths]] in the 360s.{{sfn|Heather|1998|p=85}}

Meanwhile, from 313 under the [[Edict of Milan]], the Roman Empire began to transform itself into a Christian state.{{sfn|Pop|1999|p=29}} Roman emperors supported Christian missionaries in the lands dominated by the Goths from the 340s.{{sfn|Heather|1998|p=60}} The [[Huns]] destroyed all these territories between 376 and 406, but their empire also collapsed in 453.{{sfn|Heather|1998|pp=97, 124}} Thereafter the [[Gepids]] dominated Banat, [[Crișana]], and Transylvania.{{sfn|Todd|2003|pp=220, 223}} The [[Bulgars]], [[Antes people|Antes]], [[Sclavenes]] and other tribes made frequent raids across the Lower Danube against the Balkans in the 6th&nbsp;century.{{sfn|Curta|2001|pp=115-116}} The Roman Empire revived under Emperor [[Justinian I]] (''r.'' 527&ndash;565),{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=45}} but the [[Pannonian Avars|Avars]], who had subjugated the Gepids,{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=122}} invaded the Balkans from the 580s.{{sfn|Fine|1991|pp=30-31}} In 30 years all Roman troops were withdrawn from the peninsula, where only [[Dyrrhachium]], [[Thessaloniki]] and a few other towns remained under Roman rule.{{sfn|Fine|1991|pp=35, 41}}

The next arrivals, the Bulgars, established their own state on the Lower Danube in 681.{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=67}} Their territorial expansion accelerated after the collapse of the [[Avar Khaganate]] in the 790s.{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|pp=133-134}} The ruler of the [[First Bulgarian Empire]], [[Boris I of Bulgaria|Boris I]] (''r.'' 852&ndash;889) converted to Christianity in 864.{{sfn|Fine|1991|pp=108, 118, 296}} A synod of the [[Bulgarian Orthodox Church]] promoted a [[Christian liturgy|liturgy]] in Old Church Slavonic in 893.{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=130}} Bulgaria was invaded by the Magyars (or [[Hungarians]]) in 894,{{sfn|Engel|2001|pp=9, 11-12}} but a joint counter-attack by the Bulgars and the [[Pechenegs]]{{spaced ndash}}a nomadic Turkic people{{spaced ndash}}forced the Magyars to find a new homeland in the Carpathian Basin.{{sfn|Fine|1991|pp=138-139}} Historians still debate whether they encountered a [[Romania in the Early Middle Ages#Dark Ages#Between Avars and Hungarians (c. 600–c. 900)|Romanian population]] in the territory.{{sfn|Pop|1999|p=38}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|pp=117-118}} The Byzantines occupied the greater part of Bulgaria under Emperor [[John I Tzimiskes]] (''r.'' 969&ndash;976).{{sfn|Treadgold|1997|pp=508-510, 859}} The Bulgars regained their independence during the reign of [[Samuel of Bulgaria|Samuel]] (''r.'' 997&ndash;1014),{{sfn|Treadgold|1997|pp=510, 871}} but Emperor [[Basil II]] of Byzantium conquered their country around 1018.{{sfn|Curta|2006|pp=xx, 244-245}}

The first bishop consecrated for the Hungarians was a Greek from [[Constantinople]],{{sfn|Stephenson|2000|pp=39-40}} but their supreme ruler, [[Stephen I of Hungary|Stephen]], was baptized according to the [[Western Church|Western rite]].{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=26}} Crowned the first king of Hungary in 1000 or 1001, he expanded his rule over new territories, including Banat.{{sfn|Engel|2001|pp=26-27}} {{sfn|Georgescu|1991|pp=15-16}}{{sfn|Pop|1999|pp=40-41}}{{sfn|Stephenson|2000|p=65}} Pecheneg groups, pushed by the [[Ouzes]]{{spaced ndash}}a coalition of Turkic nomads{{spaced ndash}}sought asylum in the Byzantine Empire in the 1040s.{{sfn|Curta|2006|pp=298-299}} After the Ouzes there followed the [[Cumans]]{{spaced ndash}}also a Turkic confederation{{spaced ndash}}who took control of the Pontic steppes in the 1070s.{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|pp=154-155}}{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=306}} Thereafter, specific groups, including the Hungarian-speaking [[Székelys]] and the Pechenegs, defended the frontiers of the [[Kingdom of Hungary]] against them.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=74}} The arrival of mostly [[Transylvanian Saxons|German-speaking colonists]] in the 1150s also reinforced the Hungarian monarch's rule in the region.{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=16}}{{sfn|Kristó|2003|pp=115-117, 129-131}}

The Byzantine authorities introduced new taxes, provoking an [[Vlach-Bulgarian Rebellion|uprising in the Balkan Mountains in 1185]].{{sfn|Stephenson|2000|p=289}} The local Bulgarians and Vlachs achieved their independence and established the [[Second Bulgarian Empire]] in coalition with the Cumans.{{sfn|Pop|1999|p=40}} A chieftain of the western Cuman tribes accepted Hungarian supremacy in 1227.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=95}} The Hungarian expansion towards the Pontic steppes was halted by the [[Mongol invasion of Europe|large Mongol campaign against Eastern and Central Europe]] in 1241.{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=404}} Although the Mongols withdrew in a year, their invasion caused destruction throughout the region.{{sfn|Pop|1999|p=44}}

The unification of [[Foundation of Wallachia|small polities ruled by local Romanian leaders]] in [[Oltenia]] and [[Muntenia]]{{sfn|Pop|1999|p=44}} led to the establishment of a new principality, [[Wallachia]].{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=17}} It achieved independence under [[Basarab I of Wallachia|Basarab the Founder]], who defeated a Hungarian army in the [[battle of Posada]] in 1330.{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=17}} A second principality, [[Moldavia]], became independent in the 1360s under [[Bogdan I of Moldavia|Bogdan I]], a Romanian nobleman from [[Maramureș]].{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=18}}

==Theories on the Romanians' ethnogenesis==

[[File:Map Length of Roman Rule Neo Latin Languages.jpg|thumb|right|Length of Roman rule and distribution of modern [[Romance languages]]. Romanian is the only Romance language which is spoken primarily in territories which were never or only for about 170 years under Roman rule.]]

One of the first scholars who systematically studied the [[Romance languages]], [[Friedrich Christian Diez]], described Romanian as a semi-Romance language in the 1830s.{{sfn|Posner|1996|p=4}} In 2009, Kim Schulte likewise argued that "Romanian is a language with a hybrid vocabulary".{{sfn|Schulte|2009|p=250}} The proportion of loanwords in Romanian is indeed higher than in other Romance languages.{{sfn|Pei|1976|p=143}} Its certain structural features{{mdash}}such as the construction of the future tense{{mdash}}also distinguish Romanian from other Romance languages.{{sfn|Pei|1976|p=143}} The [[Balkan sprachbund|same peculiarities]] connect it to [[Albanian language|Albanian]], [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] and other tongues spoken in the Balkan Peninsula.{{sfn|Petrucci|1999|p=9}} Nevertheless, as linguist Graham Mallinson emphasizes, Romanian "retains enough of its Latin heritage at all linguistic levels to qualify for membership of the Romance family in its own right", even without taking into account the "re-Romancing tendency" during its recent history.{{sfn|Mallinson|1988|p=418}} The core vocabulary is to a large degree Latin, including the most frequently used 2500 words.{{sfn|Boia|2004|p=54}}{{sfn|Pană Dindelegan|2013|p=3}} Around one-fifth of the entries of the 1958 edition of the ''Dictionary of the Modern Romanian'' have directly been inherited from Latin.{{sfn|Mallinson|1988|p=417}} More than 75% of the words in the semantic fields of sense perception, quantity, kinship and spatial relations are of Latin origin, but the basic lexicons of religion and of agriculture have also been preserved.{{sfn|Schulte|2009|pp=239, 243-244}}{{sfn|Spinei|2009|pp=224, 269}} 

Romanians, known by the [[exonym]] [[Vlachs]] in the Middle Ages,{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=15}} speak a language descended from the [[Vulgar Latin]] that was once spoken in south-eastern Europe.{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=276}}{{sfn|Petrucci|1999|p=4}} Inscriptions from the Roman period prove that a line, known as the "[[Jireček Line]]", can be drawn through the [[Balkan Peninsula]], which separated the Latin-speaking northern provinces, including Dacia, Moesia and [[Pannonia (Roman province)|Pannonia]] from the southern regions where Greek remained the predominant language.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=128}} [[Eastern Romance languages|Eastern Romance]] now has four variants,{{sfn|Mallinson|1988|p=392}} which are former dialects of a [[Proto-Romanian language]].{{sfn|Augerot|2009|p=901}}{{sfn|Mišeska Tomić|2006|p=39}} [[Romanian language|Daco-Romanian]], the official language of Romania, is the most widespread of the four variants.{{sfn|Augerot|2009|p=901}} Speakers of the [[Aromanian language]] live in scattered communities in Albania, Bulgaria, Greece and Macedonia.{{sfn|Augerot|2009|p=901}} Another two, by now nearly extinct variants, [[Megleno-Romanian language|Megleno-Romanian]] and [[Istro-Romanian language|Istro-Romanian]], are spoken in some villages in Macedonia and Greece, and in Croatia, respectively.{{sfn|Augerot|2009|p=901}}  Aromanian and Megleno-Romanian are spoken in the central and southern regions of the Balkans, indicating that they migrated to these territories in the Middle Ages.{{sfn|Mišeska Tomić|2006|p=40}}{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=320}} Some variants of the [[Eastern Romance languages]] retained more elements of their Latin heritage than others.<ref group="note">For instance, both the [[Maramureș subdialect of Romanian]] and Arumanian have preserved the Latin word for sand (''arină'') instead of standard ''nisip'', a Slavic loanword.</ref>{{sfn|Mallinson|1988|p=412}}{{sfn|Mišeska Tomić|2006|p=665}}

The territories south of the Danube were subject to the Romanization process for about 800 years, while Dacia province to the north of the river was only for 165 years under Roman rule, which caused "a certain disaccord between the effective process of Roman expansion and [[Romanization (cultural)|Romanization]] and the present ethnic configuration of Southeastern Europe", according to [[Lucian Boia]].{{sfn|Boia|2001|pp=113-114}} Political and ideological considerations, including the dispute between Hungary and Romania over [[Transylvania]], have also colored these scholarly discussions.{{sfn|Schramm|1997|pp=276, 280}}{{sfn|Hitchins|2014|p=17}} Accordingly, theories on the Romanian ''[[Urheimat]]'' or "homeland" can be divided into two or more groups, including the theory of Daco-Roman continuity of the continuous presence of the Romanians' ancestors in the lands north of the Lower Danube and the opposite immigrationist theory.{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=276}}{{sfn|Petrucci|1999|p=4}} Independently of the theories, a number of scholars propose that Romanian developed from the tongue of a bilingual population, because bilingualism is the most probable explanation for its peculiarities.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=131}}{{sfn|Petrucci|1999|p=141}}{{sfn|Schulte|2009|p=235}}{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=335}}

===Historiography: origin of the theories===

[[Byzantine literature|Byzantine authors]] were the first to write of the Romanians (or Vlachs).{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=13}} The 11th-century scholar [[Kekaumenos]] wrote of a Vlach homeland situated "near the Danube and&nbsp;[...]&nbsp;the Sava, where the Serbians lived more recently".{{sfn|Madgearu|2005a|p=56}}<ref>''Cecaumeno: Consejos de un aristócrata bizantino'' (12.4.2), p. 122.</ref> He associates the Vlachs with the Dacians and the [[Bessi]] and with the Dacian king [[Decebal]].{{sfn|Madgearu|2005a|pp=56-57}} Accordingly, historians have located this homeland in several places, including [[Pannonia Inferior]] ([[Bogdan Petriceicu Hașdeu]]) and "Dacia Aureliana" (Gottfried Schramm).{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=323}}{{sfn|Madgearu|2005a|p=56}} When associating the Vlachs with ancient ethnic groups, Kekaumenos followed the the practice of Byzantine authors who named contemporary peoples for peoples known from ancient sources.{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=215}} The 12th-century scholar [[John Kinnamos]] wrote that the Vlachs "are said to be formerly colonists from the people of Italy".{{sfn|Kristó|2003|p=139}}{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=132}}<ref>''Deeds of John and Manuel Comnenus by John Kinnamos'' (6.3.260), p. 195.</ref> [[William of Rubruck]] wrote that the Vlachs of Bulgaria descended from the ''Ulac'' people,<ref>''The Mission of Friar William of Rubruck'' (21.3.), p. 139.</ref> who lived beyond [[Bashkirs|Bashkiria]].{{sfn|Spinei|2009|pp=77-78}} Rubruck's words imply that he regarded the Vlachs a migrant population, coming from the region of the Volga like their Hungarian and Bulgarian neighbors.{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=78}} The late 13th-century Hungarian chronicler [[Simon of Kéza]] states that the Vlachs used to be the Romans' "shepherds and husbandmen" who "elected to remain behind in Pannonia"<ref>''Simon of Kéza: The Deeds of the Hungarians'' (chapter 14.), p. 55.</ref> when the Huns arrived.{{sfn|Madgearu|2005a|pp=46-47}} An unknown author's ''Description of Eastern Europe'' from 1308 likewise states that the Balkan Vlachs "were once the [[shepherds of the Romans]]" who "had over them ten powerful kings in the entire [[Moesia|Messia]] and Pannonia".{{sfn|Madgearu|2005a|pp=54-55}}{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=76}}

[[Poggio Bracciolini]], an Italian scholar was the first to write (around 1450) that the Romanians' ancestors had been Roman colonists settled in Dacia Traiana.{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=4}} In 1458, [[Aeneas Sylvius Piccolomini]] stated in his work ''De Europa'' (1458) that the Vlachs were a ''genus Italicum'' ("an Italian race")<ref>''Aeneas Silvius Piccolomini: Europe'' (ch. 2.14.), p. 65.</ref> and were named after one Pomponius Flaccus, a commander sent against the Dacians.{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=5}} Piccolomini's version of the Vlachs' origin from Roman settlers in Dacia Traiana was repeated by many scholars{{mdash}}including the Italian [[Flavio Biondo]] and [[Pietro Ranzano]], the Transylvanian Saxon Johannes Lebelius and the Hungarian [[Stephan Szántó]]{{mdash}}in the subsequent century.{{sfn|Almási|2010|pp=107, 109-109}}{{sfn|Armbruster |1972|p=61}} On the other hand, [[Laonikos Chalkokondyles]]{{mdash}}a late-15th-century Byzantine scholar{{mdash}}stated that he never heard anyone "explain clearly where" the Romanians "came from to inhabit" their lands.{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=19}} Chalkokondyles also wrote that the Romanians were said to have come "from many places and settled that area".<ref>''Laonikos Chalkokondyles: Demonstrations of Histories'', p. 203.</ref> The 17th-century [[Johannes Lucius]] expressed his concerns about the survival of Romans in the territory of the former Dacia Traiana province, exposed to invasions for a millennium.{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=19}}

A [[Foundation of Moldavia#'Dismounting' by Dragoş|legend on the origin of the Moldavians]], preserved in the ''Moldo-Russian Chronicle'' from around 1505,{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=11}}{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=197}} narrates that one "King Vladislav of Hungary" invited their Romanian ancestors to his kingdom and settled them "in Maramureş between the ''Moreş'' and Tisa at a place called ''Crij''".{{sfn|Vékony|2000|pp=11-13}} ''[[Logothete|Logofăt]]'' Istratie and other 17th-century Moldavian historians continued to credit "King Vladislav" with the settlement of the Romanians' ancestors in Maramureş.{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=13}} [[Grigore Ureche]]'s  ''Chronicle of Moldavia'' of 1647{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=69}} is the first Romanian historical work stating that the Romanians "all come from ''Rîm''" (Rome).{{sfn|Boia|2001|p=85}}{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=14}} In 30 years [[Miron Costin]] explicitly connected the Romanians' [[ethnogenesis]] to the conquest of "Dacia Traiana".{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|pp=69-70}} [[Constantin Cantacuzino (stolnic)|Constantin Cantacuzino]] stated in 1716 that the native Dacians also had a role in the formation of the Romanian people.{{sfn|Boia|2001|p=85}}{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=16}} [[Petru Maior]] and other historians of the "[[Transylvanian School]]" flatly denied any interbreeding between the natives and the conquerors, claiming that the autochthonous Dacian population which was not eradicated by the Romans fled the territory.{{sfn|Boia|2001|pp=85-86}} The Daco-Roman mixing became widely accepted in the Romanian historiography around 1800. This view is advocated by the Greek-origin historians [[Dimitrie Philippide]] (in his 1816 work ''History of Romania'') and [[Dionisie Fotino]], who wrote ''History of Dacia'' (1818).{{sfn|Boia|2001|p=86}}{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=116}} The idea was accepted and taught in the [[Habsburg Monarchy]], including Hungary until the 1870s,{{sfn|Pohl|2013|pp=23-24}} although the Austrian Franz Joseph Sulzer had by the 1780s rejected any form of continuity north of the Danube, and instead proposed a 13th-century migration from the Balkans.{{sfn|Vékony|2000|pp=19-20}}

The development of the theories was closely connected to political debates in the {{nobr|18th century}}.{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=12}}{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=22}}{{sfn|Deletant|1992|p=134}} Sulzer's theory of the Romanians' migration was apparently connected to his plans on the annexation of Wallachia and Moldavia by the Habsburg Monarchy, and the settlement of German colonists in both principalities.{{sfn|Holban|2000|pp=20, 23, 456, 460, 474}} The three political "nations" of the [[Principality of Transylvania (1711–1867)|Principality of Transylvania]] (the Hungarians, Saxons and Székelys) enjoyed special privileges, while local legislation emphasized that the Romanians had been "admitted into the country for the public good" and they were only "tolerated for the benefit of the country".{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=22}}{{sfn|Prodan|1971|p=12}} When suggesting that the Romanians of Transylvania were the direct descendants of the Roman colonists in Emperor Trajan's Dacia, the historians of the "Transylvanian School" also demanded that the Romanians were to be regarded as the oldest residents of the country.{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=22}}{{sfn|Deletant|1992|pp=134-135}} The ''[[Supplex Libellus Valachorum]]''{{spaced ndash}}a petition completed by the representatives of the local Romanians in 1791{{spaced ndash}}explicitly demanded that the Romanians should be granted the same legal status that the three privileged "nations" had enjoyed because the Romanians were of Roman stock.{{sfn|Deletant|1992|p=135}}{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=91}}

===Theory of Daco-Roman continuity===

[[File:Vatra.jpg|left|thumb|The Romanians' homeland (horizontal red lines in center) and their migrations (red arrows) in the 4th-7th centuries (a map presenting views proposed by scholars who accept the "continuity" theory)<ref group="note">The map also depicts the "Jireček Line" (yellow), the Latin- and Greek-speaking territories (pink and blue areas, respectively), and the Albanians' supposed homeland (yellow areas).</ref>|215x215px]]

Scholars supporting the continuity theory argue that the Romanians descended primarily from the inhabitants of "[[Dacia Traiana]]", the province encompassing three or four [[Historical regions of Romania|regions of present-day Romania]] to the north of the Lower Danube from 106.{{sfn|Hitchins|2014|pp=17-18}} In these scholars' view, the close contacts between the autochthonous Dacians and the Roman colonists led to the formation of the Romanian people because masses of provincials stayed behind after the [[Roman Empire]] [[Aurelian Retreat|abandoned the province]] in the early 270s.{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|pp=7-8}}{{sfn|Pop|1999|pp=22-23, 28}}{{sfn|Brezeanu|1998|p=50}} Thereafter the process of Romanization expanded to the neighboring regions due to the free movement of people across the former imperial borders.{{sfn|Pop|1999|p=29}}{{sfn|Brezeanu|1998|p=52}} The spread of Christianity contributed to the process, since Latin was the [[Sacred language|language of liturgy]] among the Daco-Romans.{{sfn|Pop|1999|p=29}} The Romans held bridgeheads norths of the Lower Danube, keeping Dacia within their sphere of influence uninterruptedly until 376.{{sfn|Brezeanu|1998|p=51}}{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=10}} Proponents of the theory argues that the north-Danubian regions remained the main "center of Romanization" after the Slavs started assimilating the Latin-speaking population in the lands south of the river, or forcing them to move even further south in the 7th century.{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|pp=12-13}}{{sfn|Pop|1999|pp=32-33}}{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|pp=131-132}} Although for a millennium [[Romania in the Early Middle Ages|migratory peoples invaded the territory]], a sedentary Christian [[Romance languages|Romance-speaking]] population survived, primarily in the densely forested areas, separated from the "heretic" or pagan invaders.{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=11}}{{sfn|Pop|1999|pp=30-31}} {{sfn|Brezeanu|1998|p=61}} Only the "semisedentarian" Slavs exerted some influence on the Romanians' ancestors, especially after they adopted Orthodox Christianity in the 9th century.{{sfn|Pop|1999|pp=32-33}}{{sfn|Brezeanu|1998|pp=58-59, 61}} They played the role in the Romanians' ethnogenesis that the Germanic peoples had played in the formation of other Romance peoples.{{sfn|Pop|1999|pp=32-33}}{{sfn|Brezeanu|1998|pp=58-59, 61}}{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=131}}

Historians who accept the continuity theory emphasize that the Romanians "form the numerically largest people" in southeastern Europe.{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=10}}{{sfn|Brezeanu|1998|p=45}}{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=108}}{{sfn|Sala|2005|p=13}} Romanian ethnographers point at the "striking similarities" between the traditional Romanian folk dress and the Dacian dress depicted on [[Trajan's Column]] as a clear evidence for the connection between the ancient Dacians and modern Romanians.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Velcescu|first=Leonard|date=2011|title=Reprezentările sculpturale de Daci în Forul lui Traian (Roma) şi importanţa lor pentru cultura română  (Les représentations sculpturales de Daces du Forum de Trajan (Rome) et leur importance pour la culture roumaine)|url=|journal=Antichitatea Clasica şi Noi|volume=|pages=294-315|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=ETNOGRAFIA POPORULUI ROMAN|last=Prof. Dr. Praoveanu|first=Ioan|publisher=Paralela 45|year=2004|isbn=|location=Brasov|pages=2-7}}</ref> They also highlight the importance of the massive and organized colonization of Dacia Traiana.{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=6}}{{sfn|Pop|1999|p=22}}{{sfn|Sala|2005|p=10}} One of them, Coriolan H. Opreanu underlines that "nowhere else has anyone defied reason by stating that a [Romance] people, twice as numerous as any of its neighbours..., is only accidentally inhabiting the territory of a former Roman province, once home to a numerous and strongly Romanized population".{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=108}} With the colonists coming from many provinces and living side by side with the natives, Latin must have emerged as their common language.{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=6}}{{sfn|Pop|1999|p=22}}{{sfn|Sala|2005|pp=10-11}} The Dacians willingly adopted the conquerors' superior culture and they spoke Latin as native tongue after two or three generations.{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=7}}{{sfn|Pop|1999|pp=23-28}} Estimating the provincials' number at 500,000-1,000,000 in the 270s, supporters of the continuity theory rule out the possibility that masses of Latin-speaking commoners abandoned the province when the Roman troops and officials left it.{{sfn|Brezeanu|1998|p=50}}{{sfn|Pop|1999|p=28}}{{sfn|Hitchins|2014|p=17}} Historian Ioan-Aurel Pop concludes that the relocation of hundreds of thousands of people across the Lower Danube in a short period was impossible, especially because the commoners were unwilling to "move to foreign places, where they had nothing of their own and where the lands were already occupied."{{sfn|Pop|1999|p=28}} Romanian historians also argue that Roman sources failed to mention that the whole population was moved from Dacia Traiana.{{sfn|Hitchins|2014|p=17}} 

Most Romanian scholars accepting the continuity theory regard the archaeological evidence for the uninterrupted presence of a Romanized population in the lands now forming Romania undeniable.{{sfn|Pop|1999|p=28}}{{sfn|Brezeanu|1998|pp=52, 62}}{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|pp=8-10}}{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=127}} Especially, artefacts bearing Christian symbolism, hoards of bronze Roman coins and Roman-style pottery are listed among the archaeological finds verifying the theory.{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=10}}{{sfn|Brezeanu|1998|pp=51-52, 54-55}} The same scholars emphasize that the Romanians directly inherited the basic Christian terminology from Latin, which also substantiates the connection between Christian objects and the Romanians' ancestors.{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|pp=pp=10-11}}{{sfn|Brezeanu|1998|p=56}} Other scholars who support the same theory underline that the connection between certain artefacts or [[Assemblage (archaeology)|archaeological assemblages]] and ethnic groups is uncertain.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=127}}{{sfn|Madgearu|2005b|pp=104-105}} Instead of archaeological evidence, Alexandru Madgearu highlights the importance of the linguistic traces of continuity, referring to the Romanian river names in the [[Apuseni Mountains]] and the preservation of archaic Latin lexical elements in the local dialect.{{sfn|Madgearu|2005b|p=105}} The survival of the names of the largest rivers from Antiquity is often cited as an evidence for the continuity theory,{{sfn|Felecan|Felecan|2015|p=259}}{{sfn|Sala|2005|p=17}} although some linguists who support it notes that a Slavic-speaking population transmitted them to modern Romanians.{{sfn|Tomescu|2009|p=2728}} Some words directly inherited from Latin are also said to prove the continuous presence of the Romanians' ancestors north of the Danube, because they refer to things closely connected to these regions.{{sfn|Sala|2005|pp=22-23}} For instance, linguists [[Grigore Nandriș]] and Marius Sala argue that the Latin words for natural oil, gold and bison could only be preserved in the lands to the north of the river.{{sfn|Nandris|1951|p=16}}{{sfn|Sala|2005|pp=22-23}}

Written sources did not mention the Romanians, either those who lived north of the Lower Danube or those living to the south of the river, for centuries.{{sfn|Brezeanu|1998|pp=47-48}} Scholars supporting the continuity theory notes that the silence of sources does not contradict it, because early medieval authors named the foreign lands and their inhabitants after the ruling peoples.{{sfn|Brezeanu|1998|pp=47-48}} Hence, they mentioned Gothia, Hunia, Gepidia, Avaria, Patzinakia and Cumania, and wrote of Goths, Huns, Gepids, Avars, Pechenegs and Cumans, without revealing the multi-ethnic character of these realms.{{sfn|Brezeanu|1998|pp=47-48}} References to the ''Volokhi'' in the ''Russian Primary Chronicle'', and to the ''Blakumen'' in Scandinavian sources are often listed as the first records of north-Danubian Romanians.{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=14}}{{sfn|Madgearu|2005b|pp=51-54}}{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=139}} The ''Gesta Hungarorum''{{mdash}}the oldest extant Hungarian chronicle{{mdash}}mentioned the Vlachs and the "shepherds of the Romans" (along with the Bulgarians, Slavs, Greeks and other peoples) among the inhabitants of the Carpathian Basin at the time of the arrival of the Magyars (or Hungarians) in the late 9th century; [[Simon of Kéza]]'s later Hungarian chronicle identified the Vlachs as the "Romans shepherds and husbandman" who remained in Pannonia.{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=14}}{{sfn|Madgearu|2005b|pp=46-47}} {{sfn|Pop|1999|p=37}} Pop concludes that the two chronicles "assert the Roman origin of Romanians... by presenting them as the Romans' descendants" who stayed in the former Roman provinces.{{sfn|Pop|1999|p=36}}

===Immigrationist theory===

[[File:Map Romanian Dawns.jpg|thumb|right|The Romanians' homeland and their medieval migrations (a map presenting views proposed by scholars who accept the "immigrationist theory")|215x215px]]

Scholars who support the immigrationist theory propose that the Romanians descended from the Romanized inhabitants of the provinces to the south of the Danube.{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=326}}{{sfn|Izzo|1986|pp=144-145}}{{sfn|Boia|2001|pp=47, 113, 114}} Following the collapse of the empire's frontiers around 620, some of this population moved south to regions where Latin had not been widely spoken.{{sfn|Schramm|1997|pp=304, 309}} Others took refuge in the [[Balkan Mountains]] where they adopted an itinerant form of sheep- and goat-breeding, giving rise to the modern [[Vlach]] shepherds.{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=326}} Their mobile lifestyle contributed to their spread in the mountainous zones.{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=326}}{{sfn|Makkai|1994|p=186}} The start of their northward migration cannot exactly be dated, but they did not settle in the lands north to the Lower Danube before the end of the 10th century and they crossed the Carpathians after the mid-12th century.{{sfn|Schramm|1997|pp=340-342}}

Immigrationist scholars emphasize that all other Romance languages developed in regions which had been under Roman rule for more than 500 years and nothing suggests that Romanian was an exception.{{sfn|Izzo|1986|p=143}}{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=288}} Even in Britain, where the Roman rule lasted for 365 years (more than twice as long as in Dacia Traiana) the pre-Roman languages survived.{{sfn|Izzo|1986|p=143}} Proponents of the theory have not developed a consensual view about the Dacians' fate after the Roman conquest, but they agree that the presence of a non-Romanized rural population (either the remnants of the local Dacians, or immigrant tribesmen) in Dacia Traiana is well-documented.{{sfn|Schramm|1997|pp=290, 292-295}}{{sfn|Vékony|2000|pp=120-123}} The same scholars find it hard to believe that the Romanized elements preferred to stay behind when the Roman authorities announced the withdrawal of the troops from the province and offered the civilians to also move to the Balkans.{{sfn|Izzo|1986|p=143}}{{sfn|Schramm|1997|pp=297-298}} Furthermore, the Romans had started fleeing from Dacia Traiana decades before it was abandoned.{{sfn|Vékony|2000|pp=121, 127, 135, 139}}

Almost no place name has been preserved in the former province (while more than twenty settlements still bear a name of Roman origin in England).{{sfn|Izzo|1986|p=143}} The present forms of the few river names inherited from Antiquity show that non-Latin-speaking populations{{mdash}}Dacians and Slavs{{mdash}}mediated them to the modern inhabitants of the region.{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=292}} Both literary sources and archaeological finds confirm this conjecture: the presence of Carpians, Vandals, Taifals, Goths, Gepids, Huns, Slavs, Avars, Bulgarians and Hungarians in the former Roman province in the early Middle Ages is well documented.{{sfn|Vékony|2000|pp=155-156, 159-163, 167, 170-171, 173}} Sporadic references to few Latin-speaking individuals{{mdash}}merchants and prisoners of war{{mdash}}among the Huns and Gepids in the 5th century does not contradict this picture.{{sfn|Vékony|2000|pp=160-161, 167}} Since Eastern Germanic peoples inhabited the lands to the north of the Lower Danube for more than 300 years, the lack of loanwords borrowed from them also indicates that the Romanians' homeland was located in other regions.{{sfn|Izzo|1986|p=143}}{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=295}} Likewise, no early borrowings from Eastern or Western Slavic languages can be proven, although the Romanians' ancestors should have had much contact with Eastern and Western Slavs to the north of the Danube.{{sfn|Izzo|1986|p=144}}

Immigrationist scholars underline that the population of the Roman provinces to the south of the Danube was "thoroughly Latinized".{{sfn|Izzo|1986|p=144}} Romanian has common features with idioms spoken in the Balkans (especially with Albanian and Bulgarian), suggesting that these languages developed side by side for centuries.{{sfn|Izzo|1986|p=144}}{{sfn|Schramm|1997|pp=308, 315-316, 320-322}} Southern Slavic loanwords also abound in Romanian.{{sfn|Izzo|1986|p=144}} Literary sources attest the presence of significant Romance-speaking groups in the Balkans (especially in the mountainous regions) in the Middle Ages.{{sfn|Schramm|1997|pp=322-324}}{{sfn|Vékony|2000|pp=206-209, 211-215}} Dozens of place names of Romanian origin can still be detected in the same territory.{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=323}} The Romanians became Orthodox Christians and adopted [[Old Church Slavonic]] as liturgical language, which could hardly happen in the lands to the north of the Danube after 864 (when [[Boris I of Bulgaria]] converted to Christianity).{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=337}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|pp=117-118}} Early medieval documents unanimously describe the Vlachs as a mobile pastoralist population.{{sfn|Schramm|1997|pp=326-329}} Slavic and Hungarian loanwords also evince that the Romanians' ancestors adopted a settled way of life only at a later phase of their ethnogenesis.{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=309}}

Reliable sources refer to the Romanians' presence in the lands to the north of the Danube for the first time in the 1160s. No place names of Romanian origin were recorded where early medieval settlements existed in this area.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=118}} Here, the Romanians adopted Hungarian, Slavic and German toponyms, also indicating that they arrived after the Saxons settled in southern Transylvania in the mid-12th century.{{sfn|Engel|2001|pp=118-119}}{{sfn|Schramm|1997|pp=339-341}} The Romanians initially formed scattered communities in the Southern Carpathians, but their northward expansion is well-documented from the second half of the 13th century.{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=342}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|pp=119, 270}} Both the monarchs and individual landowners (including Roman Catholic prelates) promoted their immigration, because the Romanian sheep-herders strengthened the defense of the borderlands and colonised areas which could not be brought into agricultural cultivation.{{sfn|Engel|2001|pp=270-271}}{{sfn|Makkai|1994|pp=195-197}} The Romanians adopted a sedentary way of life after they started settling on the edge of lowland villages in the mid-14th century.{{sfn|Makkai|1994|pp=214-215}} Their immigration continued  during the following centuries and they gradually took possession of the settlements in the plains which had been depopulated by frequent incursions.{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=343}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=331}}

===Admigration theory ===
According to the "admigration theory", proposed by [[Dimitrie Onciul]], the formation of the Romanian people occurred in the former "Dacia Traiana" province, and in the central regions of the Balkan Peninsula.{{sfn|Boia|2001|p=117}}{{sfn|Schramm|1997|pp=277-278}}{{sfn|Pană Dindelegan|2013|p=1}} However, the Balkan Vlachs' northward migration ensured that these centers remained in close contact for centuries.{{sfn|Boia|2001|p=117}}{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=278}} It's a compromise between immigrationist and continuity theories.{{sfn|Boia|2001|p=117}}

{{Quote|[Centuries] ''after the fall of the Balkan provinces, a pastoral Latin-Roman tradition served as the point of departure for a Valachian-Roman ethnogenesis. This kind of virtuality{{spaced ndash}}ethnicity as hidden potential that comes to the fore under certain historical circumstances{{spaced ndash}}is indicative of our new understanding of ethnic processes. In this light, the passionate discussion for or against Roman-Romanian continuity has been misled by a conception of ethnicity that is far too inflexible''|[[Walter Pohl|Pohl, Walter]] (1998){{sfn|Pohl|1998|p=21}}}}

==Evidence==

===Written sources===

====Romania in Antiquity and the Middle Ages====
{{Further|Dacia|Dacia Traiana|Romania in the Early Middle Ages}}
[[File:Trajan's Column, Rome (14248794236).jpg|alt=Trajan's Column in Rome|thumb|302x302px|[[Trajan's Column]] in Rome]]
In the 5th century&nbsp;BC, [[Herodotus]] was the first author to write a detailed account of the natives of south-eastern Europe.{{sfn|Oltean|2007|p=41}}{{sfn|Pop|1999|p=7}} In connection with a [[Achaemenid Empire|Persian]] campaign in 514&nbsp;BC, he mentions the [[Getae]], which he called "the most courageous and upright Thracian tribe".{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=3}}<ref>''Herodotus: The Histories'' (4.93.), p. 266.</ref> [[Strabo]] wrote that the [[Dacian language|language of the Dacians]] was "the same as that of the Getae".<ref>{{cite web | last = Strabo | title = Geography | publisher = Loeb Classical Library (on LacusCurtius) | date = 2012-09-24 | url = http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/7C*.html | accessdate = 7 October 2012}}</ref>{{sfn|Oltean|2007|p=44}}

Literary tradition on the conquest of Dacia was preserved by 3-4 Roman scholars.{{sfn|Ruscu|2004|pp=75-77}} [[Cassius Dio]] wrote that "numerous Dacians kept transferring their allegiance"<ref>{{cite web | last = Cassius Dio | title = Roman History | publisher = Loeb Classical Library (on LacusCurtius) | date = 2011-04-16 | url = http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Cassius_Dio/68*.html | accessdate = 16 October 2012}}</ref> to Emperor Trajan before he commenced [[Second Dacian War|his war]] against Decebal.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=78}} [[Lucian of Samosata]], [[Eutropius (historian)|Eutropius]], and [[Julian the Apostate]] unanimously attest the memory of a "deliberate [[ethnic cleansing]]" that followed the fall of the Dacian state.{{sfn|Oltean|2007|p=55}} For instance, Lucian of Samosata who cites Emperor Trajan's physician [[Criton of Heraclea]] states that the entire Dacian "people was reduced to forty men".{{sfn|Ruscu|2004|p=77}} In fact, Thracian or possibly Dacian names represent about 2% of the approximately 3,000 proper names known from "Dacia Traiana".{{sfn|Tóth|1994|p=47}} Bitus, Dezibalos and other characteristic Dacian names were only recorded in the empire's other territories, including [[Egypt (Roman province)|Egypt]] and Italy.{{sfn|Tóth|1994|p=47}}{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=74}} [[Constantin Daicoviciu]], Dumitru Protase, Dan Ruscu and other historians have debated the validity of the tradition of the Dacians' extermination. They state that it only refers to the men's fate or comes from Eutropius's writings to provide an acceptable explanation for the massive colonisation that followed the conquest.{{sfn|Ruscu|2004|p=75}} Indeed, Eutropius also reported that Emperor Trajan transferred to the new province "vast numbers of people from all over the Roman world".{{sfn|Ruscu|2004|p=75}}<ref>''Eutropius: Breviarium'' (8.6.), p. 50.</ref> Onosmatic evidence substantiates his words: about 2,000 Latin, 420 Greek, 120 [[Illyrian languages|Illyrian]], and 70 [[Celtic languages|Celtic]] names are known from the Roman period.{{sfn|Tóth|1994|p=47}}{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=116}}

Barbarian attacks against "Dacia Traiana" were also recorded.{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=138}} For instance, "an inroad of the Carpi"<ref>{{cite web | last = [[Lactantius]] | title = Of the Manner in Which the Persecutors Died (Chapter 9) | publisher = Christian Literature Publishing Co.  (on NewAdvent)  translated in 1886 by William Fletcher; revised and edited in 2009 by Kevin Knight | url = http://www.newadvent.org/fathers/0705.htm | accessdate = 7 October 2012}}</ref> forced Emperor [[Galerius]]'s mother to flee from the province in the 240s.{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=121}} [[Aurelius Victor]], Eutropius and [[Festus (historian)|Festus]] stated that Dacia "was lost"<ref>''Aurelius Victor: De Caesaribus'' (33.), p. 33.</ref><ref>''Eutropius: Breviarium'' (9.8.), p. 57.</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Festus | title = Breviarium of the Accomplishments of the Roman People (Chapter 8) | publisher = Canisius College,  translated in 2001 by Thomas M. Banchich and Jennifer A. Meka  | url = http://www.roman-emperors.org/festus.htm | accessdate = 7 October 2012}}</ref> under Emperor [[Gallienus]] (''r.'' 253{{ndash}}268).{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=102}}{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=139}} The ''[[Augustan History]]'' and [[Jordanes]] refer to the Roman withdrawal from the province in the early 270s.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=104}} The ''Augustan History'' says that Emperor Aurelian "led away both soldiers and provincials"<ref>{{cite web | title = Historia Augusta: The Life of Aurelian (39.7.) | publisher = Loeb Classical Library (on LacusCurtius) | date = 2012-06-11 | url = http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Historia_Augusta/Aurelian/3*.html | accessdate = 7 October 2012}}</ref> from Dacia in order to repopulate [[Diocese of Illyricum|Illyricum]] and Moesia.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=104}}{{sfn|Tóth|1994|p=57}}

In less than a century, the one-time province was named "Gothia",<ref>''Paulus Orosius: The Seven Books of History against the Pagans'' (1.54.), p. 13.</ref> by authors including the 4th-century [[Orosius]].{{sfn|Bóna|1994|p=67}} The existence of Christian communities in Gothia is attested by the ''Passion'' of  [[Sabbas the Goth|Sabbas]], "a Goth by race" and by the [[martyrology|martyrologies]] of [[Wereka and Batwin]], and other Gothic Christians.{{sfn|Niculescu|2007|p=152}}{{sfn|Heather|Matthews|1991|pp=102, 104, note 38 on p 109}} Large number of Goths, [[Taifali]], and according to [[Zosimus]] "other tribes that formerly dwelt among them"<ref>{{cite web | last = Zosimus | title = New History (4.25.1) | publisher = Green and Chaplin (1814)  (on the Tertullian Project) transcribed in 2002 by Roger Pearse | url = http://www.tertullian.org/fathers/zosimus04_book4.htm | accessdate = 8 October 2012}}</ref> were admitted into the [[Eastern Roman Empire]] following the invasion of the Huns in 376.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=118}}{{sfn|Maenchen-Helfen|1973|pp=26-27}} In contrast with these peoples, the [[Carpo-Dacians]] "were mixed with the Huns".<ref>{{cite web | last = Zosimus | title = New History (4.34.6) | publisher = Green and Chaplin (1814)  (on the Tertullian Project) transcribed in 2002 by Roger Pearse | url = http://www.tertullian.org/fathers/zosimus04_book4.htm | accessdate = 8 October 2012}}</ref>{{sfn|Heather|1998|p=109}} [[Priscus of Panium]], who visited the Hunnic Empire in 448,{{sfn|Maenchen-Helfen|1973|p=479}} wrote that the empire's inhabitants spoke either Hunnic or Gothic,{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=160}} and that those who had "commercial dealings with the western Romans"<ref name='Priscus'>{{Citation|last = Bury|first = J. B.|author-link = |title = Priscus at the court of Attila |date = |year = |url = http://www9.georgetown.edu/faculty/jod/texts/priscus.html | accessdate = 8 October 2012}}</ref> also spoke Latin.{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=160}} He also mentions the local name of two drinks, ''medos'' and ''kam''.<ref name='Priscus'/>{{sfn|Maenchen-Helfen|1973|p=424}} Emperor [[Diocletian]]'s ''[[Edict on Prices]]'' states that the [[Pannonians]] had a drink named ''kamos''.{{sfn|Maenchen-Helfen|1973|p=425}} ''Medos'' may have also been an [[Illyrian languages|Illyrian]] term, but a [[Germanic languages|Germanic]] explanation cannot be excluded.{{sfn|Maenchen-Helfen|1973|p=425}}
[[File:Gesta Hungarorum Anonymous.jpg|296x296px|thumb|left|alt=Gesta Hungarorum|First page of the ''[[Gesta Hungarorum]]'']]
The 6th-century author [[Jordanes]] who called Dacia "Gepidia"<ref>''The Gothic History of Jordanes'' (12:74), p. 72.</ref>{{sfn|Wolfram|1988|p=258}} was the first to write of the Antes and Slavenes.{{sfn|Curta|2001|p=73}} He wrote that the Slavenes occupied the region "from the city of [[Noviodunum]] and the lake called Mursianus" to the river [[Dniester]], and that the Antes dwelled "in the curve of the sea of Pontus".<ref>''The Gothic History of Jordanes'' (5:35), pp. 59-60.</ref>{{sfn|Barford|2001|p=53}} [[Procopius]] wrote that the Antes and the Slaveni spoke "the same language, an utterly barbarous tongue".{{sfn|Barford|2001|p=37}}<ref>''Procopius: History of the Wars'' (7.14), p. 271.</ref> He also writes of an Antian who "spoke in the Latin tongue".{{sfn|Curta|2001|pp=79-80}}<ref>''Procopius: History of the Wars'' (7.14.33.), p. 275.</ref> The late 7th-century author [[Ananias of Shirak]] wrote in his geography that the Slavs inhabited the "large country of Dacia"<ref>''The Geography of Ananias of Şirak (L1881.3.9)'', p. 48.</ref> and formed 25 tribes.{{sfn|Bóna|1994|pp=98-99}} In 2001, Florin Curta argues, that the Slaveni ethnonym may have only been used "as an [[umbrella-term]] for various groups living north of the Danube frontier, which were neither 'Antes', nor 'Huns' or 'Avars'{{sp}}".{{sfn|Curta|2001|p=347}}

The [[Ravenna Geographer]] wrote about a Dacia "populated by the&nbsp;[...]&nbsp;Avars",{{sfn|Bóna|1994|p=92}}{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=168}}  but written sources from the 9th and 10th&nbsp;centuries are scarce.{{sfn|Curta|2006|pp=17-20}} The ''[[Royal Frankish Annals]]'' refers to the [[Abodrites]] living "in Dacia on the Danube as neighbors of the Bulgars"<ref>''Royal Frankish Annals'' (year 824), p. 116.</ref> around 824.{{sfn|Bowlus|1994|p=92}} The ''[[Bavarian Geographer]]'' locates the ''Merehanii'' next to the Bulgars.{{sfn|Bowlus|1994|p=11}} By contrast, [[Alfred the Great]] wrote of "Dacians, who were formerly Goths", living to the south-east of the "Vistula country" in his abridged translation (''ca''. 890) of [[Orosius|Paulus Orosius]]' much earlier work ''Historiae Adversus Paganos'' written around 417.{{sfn|Madgearu|2005b|pp=140-141, 187}} Emperor Constantine VII's ''[[De Administrando Imperio]]'' contains the most detailed information on the history of the region in the first decades of the 10th&nbsp;century.{{sfn|Stephenson|2000|pp=25-26}} It reveals that ''Patzinakia'',<ref>''Constantine Porphyrogenitus: De Administrando Imperio'' (ch. 37), p. 167.</ref> the Pechenegs' land was bordered by Bulgaria on the Lower Danube around 950,{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=94}} and the Hungarians lived on the rivers [[Criş River|Criş]], [[Mureș River|Mureş]], [[Timiș River|Timiş]], Tisa and ''Toutis'' at the same time.<ref>''Constantine Porphyrogenitus: De Administrando Imperio'' (ch. 40), p. 177.</ref>{{sfn|Kristó|2003|p=65}} That the Pechenegs's land was located next to Bulgaria is confirmed by the contemporary [[Abraham ben Jacob]].{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=62}}
[[File:Map_Romanian_Settling_and_Autonomy_in_Medieval_Hungary.jpg|thumb|Earliest mentions of Romanian settlements in official documents in the [[Kingdom of Hungary]] (between 1200 and 1400).|246x246px]]
The ''[[Gesta Hungarorum]]'' from around 1150 or 1200{{sfn|Madgearu|2005b|p=20}} is the first chronicle to write of Vlachs in the intra-Carpathian regions.{{sfn|Kristó|2003|pp=31-33}}{{sfn|Spinei|2009|pp=73-75}} Its anonymous author stated that the Hungarians encountered "Slavs, Bulgarians, Vlachs, and the shepherds of the Romans"<ref>''Anonymus, Notary of King Béla: The Deeds of the Hungarians'' (ch. 9.), p. 27.</ref> when invading the Carpathian Basin around 895.{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=14}} He also wrote of [[Gelou (duke)|Gelou]], "a certain Vlach"<ref>''Anonymus, Notary of King Béla: The Deeds of the Hungarians'' (ch. 24.), p. 59.</ref> ruling Transylvania, a land inhabited by "Vlachs and Slavs".<ref>''Anonymus, Notary of King Béla: The Deeds of the Hungarians'' (ch. 25.), p. 61.</ref>{{sfn|Madgearu|2005b|pp=85-89}}{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=15}} In his study on medieval Hungarian chronicles, [[Carlile Aylmer Macartney]] concluded that the ''Gesta Hungarorum'' did not prove the presence of Romanians in the territory, since its author's "manner is much rather that of a [[romantic novel]]ist than a historian".{{sfn|Macartney|1953|pp=59, 70}} In contrast, Alexandru Madgearu, in his monography dedicated to the ''Gesta'', stated that this chronicle "is generally credible", since its narration can be "confirmed by the archaeological evidence or by comparison with other written sources" in many cases.{{sfn|Madgearu|2005b|pp=147-148}}

The late 12th-century chronicle of [[Niketas Choniates]] contains another early reference to Vlachs living north of the Danube.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=56}} He wrote that they seized the future [[Byzantine emperor]], [[Andronikos I Komnenos|Andronikos Komnenos]] when "he reached the borders of Halych" in 1164.{{sfn|Kristó|2003|p=139}}<ref>''O City of Byzantium, Annals of Niketas Choniates'' (2.4.131), p. 74.</ref> Thereafter, information on Vlachs from the territory of present-day Romania abounds.{{sfn|Kristó|2003|p=140}} Choniates mentioned that the Cumans crossed the Lower Danube "with a division of Vlachs"<ref>''O City of Byzantium, Annals of Niketas Choniates'' (6.1.499), p. 275.</ref> from the north to launch a plundering raid against [[Thrace (theme)|Thrace]] in 1199.{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=141}}{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=317}} [[Pope Gregory IX]] wrote about "a certain people in the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Cumania|Cumanian bishopric]] called ''Walati''" and their bishops around 1234.{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=155}} A royal charter of 1223 confirming a former grant of land is the earliest official document of Romanians in Transylvania.{{sfn|Kristó|2003|p=140}} It refers to the transfer of land previously held by them to the [[Cârța Monastery|monastery of Cârța]], which proves that this territory had been inhabited by Vlachs before the monastery was founded.{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=354}} According to the next document, the [[Teutonic Knights]] received the right to pass through the lands possessed by the Székelys and the Vlachs in 1223. Next year the [[Transylvanian Saxons]] were entitled to use certain forests together with the Vlachs and Pechenegs.{{sfn|Kristó|2003|pp=140-141}} Simon of Kéza knew that the Székelys "shared with the Vlachs" the mountains, "mingling with them"<ref>''Simon of Kéza: The Deeds of the Hungarians'' (chapter 21.), p. 71.</ref> and allegedly adopting the Vlachs' alphabet.{{sfn|Kristó|2003|p=134}}

A charter of 1247 of King [[Béla IV of Hungary]] lists small [[Foundation of Wallachia#Earliest voivodates in medieval documents|Romanian polities]] existing north of the Lower Danube.{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=16}} [[Thomas Tuscus]] mentioned Vlachs fighting against the [[Ruthenes]] in 1276 or 1277.{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=17}}{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=131}} References to Vlachs living in the lands of secular lords and prelates in the Kingdom of Hungary appeared in the 1270s.{{sfn|Makkai|1994|p=198}} First the [[Canon (priest)|canons]] of the [[cathedral chapter]] in [[Alba Iulia]] received a royal authorization to settle Romanians to their domains in 1276.{{sfn|Kristó|2003|p=159}} Thereafter, royal charters attest the presence of Romanians in more [[County (Kingdom of Hungary)|counties]], for instance in Zărand from 1318, in [[Bihar County|Bihor]] and in [[Maramureș County|Maramureș]] from 1326, and in [[Torda County|Turda]] from 1342.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=270}} The first independent Romanian state, the [[Principality of Wallachia]], was known as ''Oungrovlachia'' ("Vlachia near Hungary") in Byzantine sources, while Moldavia received the Greek denominations ''Maurovlachia'' ("Black Vlachia") or ''Russovlachia'' ("Vlachia near Russia").{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|pp=142-143}}

====Balkan Vlachs====
{{Further|Uprising of Asen and Peter|Vlachs}}

The words ''"torna, torna fratre"''<ref>''The Chronicle of Theophanes Confessor'' (258.10-21.), p. 381.</ref> recorded in connection with a Roman campaign across the Balkan Mountains by [[Theophylact Simocatta]] and [[Theophanes the Confessor]] evidence the development of a Romance language in the late 6th century.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=129}} The words were shouted "in native parlance"<ref>''The History of Theophylact Simocatta'' (ii. 15.10.), p. 65.</ref> by a local soldier in 587 or 588.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=129}}{{sfn|Vékony|2000|pp=206-207}} When narrating the rebellion of [[Kuber]] and his people against the Avars, the 7th-century ''Miracles of St. Demetrius'' mentions that a close supporter of his, [[Mauros]]{{sfn|Curta|2006|pp=19, 106}} spoke four languages, including "our language" (Greek) and "that of the Romans" (Latin).{{sfn|Pohl|1988|pp=188, 224}} Kuber led a population of mixed origin{{spaced ndash}}including the descendants of Roman provincials{{sfn|Pohl|1998|pp=19-21}} who had been captured in the Balkans in the early 7th century{{spaced ndash}}from the region of Sirmium to Thessaloniki around 681.{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=106}}

[[File:KaloyanInnocent.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Kaloyan's letter to the pope|Letter of [[Kaloyan]], "''[[tsar]]'' of Bulgaria and Vlachia" to [[Pope Innocent III]]]]

[[John Skylitzes]]'s chronicle contains one of the earliest records on the Balkan Vlachs.{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=102}}{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=211}} He mentions that "some vagabond Vlachs"<ref>''John Skylitzes: A Synopsis of Byzantine History'' (ch. 16.), p. 312.</ref> killed [[David (noble)|David]], one of the four [[Cometopuli]] brothers between [[Kastoria]] and [[Prespa]] in 976.{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=152}}{{sfn|Vékony|2000|pp=211-212}} After the Byzantine occupation of Bulgaria, Emperor Basil II set up the [[autocephalous]] [[Archbishopric of Ohrid]] with the right from 1020 to collect income "from the Vlachs in the whole of ''[[theme (Byzantine district)|theme]]'' of [[Bulgaria (theme)|Bulgaria]]".{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=19}}{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=79}} The late 11th-century Kekaumenos relates that the Vlachs of the region of [[Larissa]] had "the custom of having their herds and families stay in high mountains and other really cold places from the month of April to the month of September".{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=280}}<ref>''Cecaumeno: Consejos de un aristócrata bizantino'' (12.3.4), p. 115.''</ref> A passing remark by [[Anna Komnene|Anna Comnena]] reveals that nomads of the Balkans were "commonly called Vlachs" around 1100.{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=215}}{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=20}}<ref>''Anna Comnena: The Alexiad'' (8.3.), p. 252.</ref> Occasionally, the Balkan Vlachs cooperated with the Cumans against the Byzantine Empire, for instance by showing them "the way through the passes"<ref>''Anna Comnena: The Alexiad'' (10.3.), p. 298.</ref> of the [[Stara Planina]] in the 1090s.{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=21}}{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=281}}

Most information on the 1185 uprising of the Bulgars and Vlachs and the subsequent establishment of the Second Bulgarian Empire is based on Niketas Choniates's chronicle.{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=358}} He states that it was "the rustling of their cattle"<ref>''O City of Byzantium, Annals of Niketas Choniates'' (5.1.368) , p. 204.</ref> which provoked the Vlachs to rebel against the imperial government.{{sfn|Stephenson|2000|p=289}}{{sfn|Curta|2006|pp=358-359}} Besides him, Ansbert, and a number of other contemporary sources refer to the Vlach origin of the [[Asen dynasty|Asen brothers]] who initiated the revolt.<ref group="note">Ansbert referred to one of the Asen brothers, [[Peter II of Bulgaria]] as "Kalopetrus Flachus".</ref>{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|pp=36-37}} The Vlachs' pre-eminent role in the Second Bulgarian Empire is demonstrated by ''Blacia'', and other similar denominations under which the new state was mentioned in contemporary sources.{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=27}} The ''[[Annales Florolivienses]]'', the first such source,{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=29}} mentions  the route of Emperor [[Frederick I Barbarossa]] "through Hungary, [[Kievan Rus'|Russia]], [[Cumania]], ''Vlakhia'', [[Durrës|Durazzo]], Byzantium and [[Sultanate of Rum|Turkey]]" during [[Third Crusade#Barbarossa's crusade|his crusade of 1189]].{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=29}} [[Pope Innocent III]] used the terms "Vlachia and Bulgaria" jointly when referring to the whole territory of the Second Bulgarian Empire.{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=30}} Similarly, the chronicler [[Geoffrey of Villehardouin]] refers to the Bulgarian ruler [[Kaloyan]] as "Johanitsa, the king of Vlachia and Bulgaria".{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=30}}<ref>''Geoffrey Villehardouin: The Conquest of Constantinople'' (6.202), p. 54.</ref>  The Icelandic author [[Snorri Sturluson]] mentioned the Balkan Vlachs' territory  as ''[[Blakumen#Blokumannaland|Blokumannaland]]'' in his early 13th-century text ''[[Heimskringla]]''.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=56}}{{sfn|Spinei|2009|pp=105-106}}  William of Rubruck distinguished Bulgaria from ''Blakia''.{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=30}} He stated that "Bulgaria, ''Blakia'' and [[Slavonia]] were provinces of the Greeks",<ref>''The Mission of Friar William of Rubruck'' (21.5.), p. 140.</ref> implying that his ''Blakia'' was also located south of the Danube.{{sfn|Vásáry|2005|p=30}} Likewise, the "Vlach lands" mentioned in the works of [[Abulfeda]], [[Ibn Khaldun]] and other medieval Muslim authors are identical with Bulgaria.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=132}}

====Uncertain references====

{{Further|Blakumen}}

The 10th-century Muslim scholars, [[Al-Muqaddasi]] and [[Ibn al-Nadim]] mentioned the ''Waladj'' and the ''Blaghā'', respectively in their lists of peoples.{{sfn|Spinei|2009|pp=82-83}} The lists also refer to the [[Khazars]], [[Alans]], and Greeks, and it is possible that the two ethnonyms refer to Vlachs dwelling somewhere in south-eastern Europe.{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=83}} For instance, historian Alexandru Madgearu says that Al-Muqaddasi's work is the first reference to Romanians living north of the Danube.{{sfn|Madgearu|1997|pp=161}}  [[Victor Spinei]] writes that a [[runestone]] which was set up around 1050 contains the earliest reference to Romanians living east of the Carpathians.{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=54}} It refers to ''[[Blakumen]]'' who killed a [[Varangian]] merchant at an unspecified place.{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=54}} The 11th-century Persan writer, [[Gardizi]], wrote about a Christian people called ''N.n.d.r'' inhabiting the lands along the Danube.{{sfn|Armbruster|1972|p=11}} Historian [[Adolf Armbruster]] identified this people as Vlachs.{{sfn|Armbruster|1972|p=11}} In Hungarian, the Bulgarians were called ''Nándor'' in the Middle Ages.{{sfn|Kristó|1996|p=63}}

The ''[[Russian Primary Chronicle]]'' from 1113 contains possible references to Vlachs in the Carpathian Basin.{{sfn|Madgearu|2005b|p=51}}{{sfn|Kristó|2003|p=31}} It relates how the ''Volokhi'' seized "the territory of the Slavs"<ref>''Russian Primary Chronicle'' (years 6396&ndash;6406), p. 62.</ref> and were expelled by the Hungarians.{{sfn|Madgearu|2005b|pp=51-53}}{{sfn|Deletant|1992|p=84}} Therefore, the Slavs' presence antedates the arrival of the ''Volokhi'' in the chronicle's narration.{{sfn|Kristó|2003|p=31}} Madgearu and many other historians argue that the ''Volokhi'' are Vlachs, but the ''Volokhi'' have also been identified with either Romans or Franks annexing Pannonia (for instance, by [[Lubor Niederle]] and by Dennis Deletant respectively).{{sfn|Kristó|2003|p=31}}{{sfn|Madgearu|2005b|pp=52-53, n45 on p. 163}}{{sfn|Deletant|1992|pp=84-85}}

The poem ''[[Nibelungenlied]]'' from the early 1200s mentions one "duke Ramunc of Wallachia"<ref>''The Nibelungenlied: The Lay of the Nibelungs'' (22.1342), p. 124.</ref> in the retinue of [[Attila the Hun]].{{sfn|Spinei|1986|p=56}}{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=355}} The poem alludes to the Vlachs along with the Russians, Greeks, Poles and [[Pechenegs]], and may refer to a "Wallachia" east of the Carpathians.{{sfn|Spinei|1986|pp=56-57}} The identification of the Vlachs and the ''[[Bolokhoveni]]'' of the ''[[Hypatian Chronicle]]'' whose land bordered on the [[Principality of Halych]] is not unanimously accepted by historians (for instance, Victor Spinei refuses it).{{sfn|Spinei|2009|pp=161-162}}

===Archaeological data===

====To the north of the Lower Danube====

