''[[Tumuli]]'' erected for a cremation rite appeared in Oltenia and in Transylvania around 100&nbsp;BC, thus preceding the emergence of the Dacian kingdom.{{sfn|Rustoiu|2005|p=45}} Their rich inventory has analogies in archaeological sites south of the Danube.{{sfn|Rustoiu|2005|p=45}} Although only around 300 graves from the next three centuries have been unearthed in Romania, they represent multiple burial rites, including ''[[ustrinum]]'' cremation{{sfn|Taylor|2001|p=405}} and [[inhumation]].{{sfn|Lockyear|2004|pp=63-65}} New villages in the Mureș valley prove a demographic growth in the 1st&nbsp;century&nbsp;BC.{{sfn|Rustoiu|2005|p=46}} Fortified settlements were erected on hilltops,{{sfn|Rustoiu|2005|p=46}} mainly in the [[Orăştie Mountains]],{{sfn|Taylor|2001|p=405}} but open villages remained the most common type of settlement.{{sfn|Lockyear|2004|p=37}} In contrast with the finds of 25,000 Roman ''[[denarii]]'' and their local copies, imported products were virtually missing in Dacia.{{sfn|Taylor|2001|p=407}} The interpretations of Geto-Dacian archaeological findings are problematic because they may be still influenced by methodological nationalism.{{sfn|Daskalov|Vezenkov|2015|p=47}}

The conquering Romans destroyed all fortresses{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=75}} and the main Dacian sanctuaries around 106 AD.{{sfn|Oltean|2007|p=227}} All villages disappeared because of the demolition.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=75}} Roman settlements built on the location of former Dacian ones have not been identified yet.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=75}} However, the rural communities at [[Boarta]], [[Cernat, Covasna|Cernat]], and other places used "both traditional and Roman items", even thereafter.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=76}} Objects representing local traditions have been unearthed at Roman villas in [[Aiudul de Sus]], [[Deva, Romania|Deva]] and other places as well.{{sfn|Oltean|2007|p=143}} A feature of the few types of native [[pottery]] which continued to be produced in Roman times is the "Dacian cup", a mostly hand-made mug with a wide rim,{{sfn|Tóth|1994|p=50}} which was used even in military centers.{{sfn|Oltean|2007|p=225}} The use of a type of tall cooking pot indicates the survival of traditional culinary practices as well.{{sfn|Oltean|2007|p=225}}

Colonization and the presence of military units gave rise to the emergence of most towns in "Dacia Traiana": for instance, [[Ulpia Traiana Sarmizegetusa]] was founded for veterans, [[Apulum (castra)|Apulum]] and [[Potaissa]] started to develop as ''[[canabae]]''.{{sfn|Oltean|2007|pp=88-89}} Towns were the only places where the presence of Christians can be assumed based on objects bearing Christian symbolism, including a lamp and a cup decorated with crosses, which have been dated to the Roman period.{{sfn|Madgearu|2004|p=41}} Rural cemeteries characterized by burial rites with analogies in sites east of the Carpathians attest to the presence of immigrant "barbarian" communities, for instance, at [[Obreja]] and [[Soporu de Câmpie]].{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=79}} Along the northwestern frontiers of the province, "[[Przeworsk culture|Przeworsk]]" settlements were unearthed at [[Boineşti]], [[Cehăluţ]], and other places.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=99}}

Archaeological finds suggest that attacks against Roman Dacia became more intensive from the middle of the 3rd&nbsp;century: an inscription from Apulum hails Emperor [[Decius]] (''r.'' 249&ndash;251) as the "restorer of Dacia"; and coin hoards ending with pieces minted in this period have been found.{{sfn|Tóth|1994|p=52}} Inscriptions from the 260s attest that the two Roman legions of Dacia were transferred to [[Pannonia Superior]] and Italy.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=103}} Coins bearing the inscription "DACIA FELIX" minted in 271 may reflect that Trajan's Dacia still existed in that year,{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=103}} but they may as well refer to the establishment of the new province of "Dacia Aureliana".{{sfn|Tóth|1994|p=55}}

The differentiation of archaeological finds from the periods before and after the Roman withdrawal is not simple, but [[Archiud]], Obreja, and other villages produced finds from both periods.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=109}} Towns have also yielded evidence on locals staying behind.{{sfn|Georgescu|1991|p=10}} For instance, in Ulpia Traiana Sarmizegatusa, at least one building was inhabited even in the 4th century, and a local factory continued to produce pottery, although "in a more restricted range".{{sfn|Oltean|2007|pp=174, 185}} Roman coins  from the 3rd and 4th&nbsp;centuries, mainly minted in bronze, were found in Banat where small Roman forts were erected in the 290s.{{sfn|Ellis|1998|pp=231-232}} Coins minted under Emperor Valentinian I (''r.'' 364&ndash;375) were also found in Ulpia Traiana Sarmizegetusa, where the gate of the [[amphitheatre|amphitheater]] was walled at an uncertain date.{{sfn|Vékony|2000|pp=144-145}} A [[Biertan Donarium|votive plate]] found near a spring at [[Biertan]] bears a Latin inscription dated to the 4th century, and has analogies in objects made in the Roman Empire.{{sfn|Madgearu|2004|pp=46, 48-49}} Whether this ''donarium'' belonged to a Christian missionary, to a local cleric or layman or to a pagan Goth making an offering at the spring is still debated by archaeologists.{{sfn|Madgearu|2004|p=47, 49}}

A new cultural synthesis, the "[[Sântana de Mureş-Chernyakhov culture]]", spread through the plains of Moldavia and Wallachia in the early 4th century.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=117}} It incorporated elements of the "[[Wielbark culture]]" of present-day Poland and of local tradition.{{sfn|Heather|1998|pp=37-38}}{{sfn|Heather|Matthews|1991|pp=88-89}} More than 150 "Sântana de Mureş-Chernyakhov" settlements{{sfn|Niculescu|2007|p=145}} suggest that the territory experienced a demographic growth.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=117}} Three sites in the Eastern Carpathians already inhabited in the previous century<ref group="note">[[Botoşana]], [[Dodeşti]], and [[Mănoaia]] ''(Heather, Matthews 1991, p. 91.)''.</ref> prove the natives' survival as well.{{sfn|Heather|Matthews|1991|pp=91-92}} Growing popularity of inhumation burials also characterizes the period.{{sfn|Ellis|1998|p=230}} "Sântana de Mureş-Chernyakhov" cemeteries from the 4th century were also unearthed in Transylvania.{{sfn|Bóna|1994|p=70}}
Coin hoards ending with pieces from the period between 375 and 395 unearthed at [[Bistreţ]], [[Gherla]], and other settlements{{sfn|Madgearu|2004|p=42}} point to a period of uncertainty.{{sfn|Bóna|1994|p=76}} Featuring elements of the "Przeworsk" and "Sântana de Mureş-Chernyakhov" cultures also disappeared around 400.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=119}} Archaeological sites from the next centuries have yielded finds indicating the existence of scattered communities bearing different traditions.{{sfn|Barford|2001|pp=43, 48-49}} Again, cremation became the most widespread burial rite east of the Carpathians, where a new type of building{{spaced ndash}}sunken huts with an oven in the corner{{spaced ndash}}also appeared.{{sfn|Barford|2001|p=48}} The heterogeneous vessel styles were replaced by the more uniform "Suceava-Şipot" [[archaeological horizon]] of hand made pottery from the 550s.{{sfn|Barford|2001|p=56}}

In contrast with the regions east of the Carpathians, Transylvania experienced the spread of the "row grave" horizon of inhumation necropolises in the 5th&nbsp;century,{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=120}} also known from the same period in Austria, [[Bohemia]], [[Transdanubia]] and [[Thuringia]].{{sfn|Bóna|1994|p=85}} At the same time, large villages appeared in Crișana and Transylvania,{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=54}} in most cases in places where no earlier habitation has yet been proven.{{sfn|Bóna|1994|p=86}} Moreover, imported objects with Christian symbols, including a fish-shaped lamp from [[Lipova, Arad|Lipova]], and a "[[Saint Menas]] flask" from [[Moigrad]], were unearthed.{{sfn|Madgearu|2004|p=46}} However, only about 15% of the 30 known "row grave" cemeteries survived until the late 7th century.{{sfn|Bóna|1994|p=89-90}} They together form the distinct "Band-Noşlac" group of graveyards{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=122}} which also produced weapons and other objects of Western or Byzantine provenance.{{sfn|Bóna|1994|p=90}}

The earliest examples in Transylvania of inhumation graves with a corpse buried, in accordance with nomadic tradition, with remains of a horse were found at [[Band, Mureş|Band]].{{sfn|Bóna|1994|p=93}} The "Gâmbaş group" of cemeteries{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=122}} emerged in the same period, producing weapons similar to those found in the Pontic steppes.{{sfn|Bóna|1994|p=94}} Sunken huts appeared in the easternmost zones of Transylvania around 7th century.{{sfn|Bóna|1994|p=99}} Soon the new horizon of "Mediaș" cemeteries,{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=122}} containing primarily cremation graves, spread along the rivers of the region.{{sfn|Barford|2001|p=76}} The "Nușfalău-Someşeni" cemeteries{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=122}} likewise follow the cremation rite, but they produced large ''[[tumuli]]'' with analogies in the territories east of the Carpathians.{{sfn|Barford|2001|p=76}}

In the meantime, the "Suceava-Şipot horizon" disappeared in Moldavia and Wallachia, and the new "[[Dridu culture]]" emerged on both sides of the Lower Danube around 700.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=127}}{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=135}} Thereafter the region again experienced demographic growth.{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=50}} For instance, the number of settlements unearthed in Moldavia grew from about 120 to about 250 from the 9th century to the 11th century.{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=193}} Few graveyards yielding artifacts similar to "Dridu cemeteries" were also founded around Alba Iulia in Transylvania.{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=135}} The nearby "Ciumbrud group" of necropolises of inhumation graves point at the presence of warriors.{{sfn|Bóna|1994|p=104}} However, no early medieval fortresses unearthed in Transylvania, including [[Cluj-Mănăştur]], [[Dăbâca]], and [[Şirioara]], can be definitively dated earlier than the 10th century.{{sfn|Madgearu|2005b|pp=114-115, 121-122, 127}}

Small inhumation cemeteries of the "Cluj group",{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=122}} characterized by "partial symbolic horse burials", appeared at several places in Banat, Crişana, and Transylvania including at [[Biharia]], [[Cluj]] and [[Timişoara]] around 900.{{sfn|Bóna|1994|p=131}} Cauldrons and further featuring items of the "[[Saltovo-Mayaki]] culture" of the Pontic steppes were unearthed in Alba Iulia, Cenad, Dăbâca, and other settlements.{{sfn|Bóna|1994|p=160}} A new custom of [[Charon's obol|placing coins on the eyes of the dead]] was also introduced around 1000.{{sfn|Bóna|1994|p=160}} "[[Bijelo Brdo culture|Bijelo Brdo]]" cemeteries, a group of large graveyards with close analogies in the whole Carpathian Basin, were unearthed at Deva, Hunedoara and other places.{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=251}} The east&ndash;west orientation of their graves may reflect Christian influence,{{sfn|Bóna|1994|p=160}} but the following "Citfalău group" of huge cemeteries that appeared in royal fortresses around 1100 clearly belong to a Christian population.{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=351}}

Romanian archaeologists propose that a series of archaeological horizons that succeeded each other in the lands north of the Lower Danube in the early Middle Ages support the continuity theory.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|pp=126-127}}{{sfn|Niculescu|2007|p=136}} In their view, archaeological finds at [[Brateiu]] (in Transylvania), [[Ipotești, Olt|Ipotești]] (in Wallachia) and [[Costișa]] (in Moldavia) represent the Daco-Roman stage of the Romanians' ethnogenesis which ended in the 6th century.{{sfn|Niculescu|2007|p=136}}{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=126}} The next ("Romanic") stage can be detected through assemblages unearthed in Ipotești, [[Botoșana]], [[Hansca]] and other places which were dated to the 7th-8th centuries.{{sfn|Niculescu|2007|p=136}} Finally, the [[Dridu culture]] is said to be the evidence for the "ancient Romanian" stage of the formation of the Romanian people.{{sfn|Niculescu|2007|p=136}} In contrast to these views, Opreanu emphasizes that the principal argument of the hypothesis{{mdash}}the presence of artefacts imported from the Roman Empire and their local copies in allegedly "Daco-Roman" or "Romanic" assemblages{{mdash}}is not convincing, because close contacts between the empire and the neighboring Slavs and Avars is well-documnted.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=127}} He also underlines that Dridu culture developed after a "cultural discontinuity" that followed the disappearance of the previous horizons.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=127}} Regarding both the Slavs and Romanians as sedentary populations, Alexandru Madgearu also underlines that the distinction of "Slavic" and "Romanian" artefacts is difficult, because archaeologists can only state that these artifacts could hardly be used by nomads.{{sfn|Madgearu|2005b|pp=104-105}} He proposes that "The wheel-made pottery produced on the fast wheel (as opposed to the tournette), which was found in several settlements of the eighth, ninth, and tenth centuries, may indicate the continuation of Roman traditions" in Transylvania.{{sfn|Madgearu|2005b|p=105}}

Thomas Nägler proposes that a separate "Ciugud culture" represents the Vlach population of southern Transylvania.{{sfn|Nägler|2005|p=215}} He also argues that two treasures from [[Cârțișoara]] and [[Făgăraș]] also point at the presence of Vlachs.{{sfn|Nägler|2005|p=215}} Both hoards contain Byzantine coins ending with pieces minted under Emperor [[John II Komnenos]] who died in 1143.{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=161}} Tudor Sălăgean proposes that these treasures point at a local elite with "at least" economic contacts with the Byzantine Empire.{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=161}} Paul Stephenson argues that Byzantine coins and jewellery from this period, unearthed at many places in Hungary and Romania, are connected to salt trade.{{sfn|Stephenson|2000|pp=42-44}}

