====Central and Northern Balkans====

Fortified settlements built on hill-tops characterized the landscape in Illyricum before the Roman conquest.{{sfn|Wilkes|1992|pp=226-227}} In addition, huts built on piles formed villages along the rivers Sava and its tributaries.{{sfn|Wilkes|1992|p=227}} Roman coins unearthed in the northwestern regions may indicate that trading contacts between the Roman Empire and Illyricum began in the 2nd century BC, but piracy, quite widespread in this period, could also contribute to their cumulation.{{sfn|Wilkes|1992|p=225}} The first Roman road in the Balkans, the [[Via Egnatia]] which linked Thessaloniki with Dyrrhachium was built in 140 BC.{{sfn|Wilkes|1992|p=212}} [[Byllis]] and Dyrrhachium, the earliest Roman [[Colonia (Roman)|colonies]] were founded a century later.{{sfn|Wilkes|1992|pp=212-213}} The Romans established a number of colonies for veterans and other towns, including [[Emona]], [[Siscia]], Sirmium and [[Iovia Botivo]], in the next four centuries.{{sfn|Mócsy|1974|pp=40, 74, 112-116, 221, 223}}

Hand-made pottery of local tradition remained popular even after potter's wheel was introduced by the Romans.{{sfn|Wilkes|1992|p=230}} Likewise, as it is demonstrated by altars dedicated to [[Illyrians#Religion|Illyrian deities]] at [[Bihać]] and [[Topusko]], native cults survived the Roman conquest. {{sfn|Wilkes|1992|p=246}} Latin inscriptions on stone monuments prove the existence of a native aristocracy in Roman times.{{sfn|Wilkes|1992|p=238}} Native settlements flourished in the mining districts in [[Upper Moesia]] up until the 4th century.{{sfn|Bartel|2004|pp=180-181}} Native names and local burial rites only disappeared in these territories in the 3rd century.{{sfn|Mócsy|1974|p=247}} In contrast, the frontier region along the Lower Danube in Moesia had already in the 1st century AD transformed into "a secure Roman-only zone" (Brad Bartel), from where the natives were moved.{{sfn|Bartel|2004|pp=178-179}}

Emperors born in Illyricum, a common phenomenon of the period,{{sfn|Wilkes|1992|p=261-262}} erected a number of imperial residences at their birthplaces.{{sfn|Mócsy|1974|p=300}} For instance, a palace was built for [[Maximianus Herculius]] near Sirmium, and another for Constantine the Great in [[Mediana]].{{sfn|Mócsy|1974|p=301}} New buildings, rich burials and late Roman inscriptions show that [[Horreum Margi]], [[Remesiana]], Siscia, [[Viminacium]], and other centers of administration also prospered under these emperors.{{sfn|Mócsy|1974|p=311, 313}} Archaeological research{{spaced ndash}}including the large cemeteries unearthed at Ulpianum and Naissus{{spaced ndash}}shows that Christian communities flourished in Pannonia and Moesia from the 4th century.{{sfn|Mócsy|1974|p=33-335}} Inscriptions from the 5th century point at Christian communities surviving the destruction brought by the Huns at Naissus, Viminacium and other towns of Upper Moesia.{{sfn|Mócsy|1974|pp=351-352}} In contrast, ''[[villa rustica|villae rusticae]]'' which had been centers of agriculture from the 1st century disappeared around 450.{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=43}} Likewise, [[Forum (Roman)|forums]], well planned streets and other traditional elements of urban architecture ceased to exist.{{sfn|Curta|2006|pp=40-42}} For instance, Sirmium "disintegrated into small hamlets emerging in urban areas that had not been in use until then" after 450.{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=40}} New fortified centers developed around newly erected Christian churches in Sirmium, [[Novae]],{{sfn|Curta|2001|p=127}} and many other towns by around 500.{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=40}} In contrast with towns, there are only two archaeological sites<ref group="note">At Novgrad in Bulgaria and at [[Slava Rusă]] in Romania  ''(Barford 2001, p. 60.)''.</ref> from this period identified as rural settlements.{{sfn|Barford|2001|p=60}}{{sfn|Curta|2001|p=147}}

Under Justinian the walls of [[Serdica]], Ulpianum and many other towns were repaired.{{sfn|Wilkes|1992|p=268}} He also had hundreds of small forts erected along the Lower Danube,{{sfn|Barford|2001|p=52}} at mountain passes across the [[Balkan Mountains]] and around Constantinople.{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=45}} Inside these forts small churches and houses were built.{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=46}} [[Pollen analysis]] suggest that the locals cultivated legumes within the walls, but no other trace of agriculture have been identified.{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=46}} They were supplied with grain, wine and oil from distant territories, as it is demonstrated by the great number of amphorae unearthed in these sites which were used to transport these items to the forts.{{sfn|Curta|2001|pp=186-188}} Most Roman towns and forts in the northern parts of the Balkans were destroyed in the 570s or 580s.{{sfn|Curta|2001|p=189}} Although some of them were soon restored, all of them were abandoned, many even "without any signs of violence", in the early 7th century.{{sfn|Curta|2001|p=189}}

The new horizon of "Komani-Kruja" cemeteries emerged in the same century.{{sfn|Wilkes|1992|p=273}} They yielded grave goods with analogies in many other regions, including belt buckles widespread in the whole [[Mediterranean Basin]], rings with Greek inscriptions, pectoral crosses, and weapons similar to "Late Avar" items.{{sfn|Curta|2001|pp=104-105}}{{sfn|Wilkes|1992|p=276}} Most of them are situated in the region of Dyrrhachium, but such cemeteries were also unearthed at [[Gradsko Municipality|Viničani]] and other settlements along the Via Egnatia.{{sfn|Curta|2001|p=104}} "Komani-Kruja" cemeteries ceased to exist in the early 9th century.{{sfn|Wilkes|1992|p=277}} John Wilkes proposes that they "most likely" represent a Romanized population,{{sfn|Wilkes|1992|p=278}} while Florin Curta emphasizes their Avar features.{{sfn|Curta|2001|p=106}} Archaeological finds connected to a Romance-speaking population have also been searched in the lowlands to the south of the Lower Danube.{{sfn|Fiedler|2008|p=158}} For instance, Uwe Fiedler mentions that inhumation graves yielding no grave goods from the period between the 680s and the 860s may represent them, although he himself rejects this theory.{{sfn|Fiedler|2008|p=158}}

