=== Linguistic approach ===

====Development of Romanian====
{{Main|History of the Romanian language}}
{{Further|Balkan sprachbund|Eastern Romance substratum|Jireček Line|Paleo-Balkan languages}}
[[File:Theoretical map of Romanian origins.png|thumb|200x200px|alt=Albanians as migrating Carps (a theory by B. P. Hasdeu)|[[Albanians]] as descendants of migrating [[Carpians]] (a theory proposed in 1905 by [[Bogdan Petriceicu Hașdeu]] to explain the similarities between the Romanian and Albanian languages within the framework of the continuity theory, by establishing a shared origin from [[Dacian language|Dacian]], with the Albanian resisting Romanization in the Roman Empire for centuries)]]

The formation of the [[Common Romanian]] language from Vulgar Latin started in the 6th or 7th centuries and was completed in the 8th century.{{sfn|Pană Dindelegan|2013|p=2}} Common Romanian split into four variants (Daco-Romanian, Macedo-Romanian, Megleno-Romanian and Istro-Romanian) during the 10th-12th centuries.{{sfn|Petrucci|1999|pp=5-6}}{{sfn|Augerot|2009|p=901}}{{sfn|Pană Dindelegan|2013|pp=3, 6}} Unlike other Romance languages, the Romanian subdialects spoken to the north of the Danube display a "remarkable unity".{{sfn|Pană Dindelegan|2013|p=6}} Primarily the use of different words differentiate them, because their [[phonology]] is quite uniform.{{sfn|Wexler|1997|p=183}} Whether the shepherds seasonal movements between the mountains and the lowlands secured the preservation of language unity,{{sfn|Pană Dindelegan|2013|p=6}} or the levelling effect of migrations gave rise to the development of a uniform idiom,<ref group="note">The development of a uniform language along the Western coasts if the USA demonstrates such a leveling effect.</ref> cannot be decided.{{sfn|Wexler|1997|p=183}}

There are [[List of Romanian words of possible Dacian origin|around 100 Romanian words]] with a possible [[Eastern Romance substratum|substratum]] origin, but the language from which they were transferred cannot be determined.{{sfn|Augerot|2009|p=901}} Around 30% of these words<ref group="note">For instance, ''cârlan''  ("yearling") [http://dexonline.ro/definitie/cârlan], and ''[[urdă]]'' ("cheese made of whey") [http://dexonline.ro/definitie/urdă] ''(Spinei 2009, p. 228.)''.</ref> represent the specific vocabulary of sheep- and goat-breeding.{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=312}} Moreover, about 70 possible substrate words,<ref group="note">Including, Romanian ''strungă'' ("sheepfold") [http://dexonline.ro/definitie/strungă] and Albanian ''shtrungë'' ("milking enclosure"), Romanian ''ţap'' [http://dexonline.ro/definitie/ţap] and Albanian ''cjap'' ("he-goat") ''(Orel 1998, pp. 47., 443.)''.</ref> have Albanian cognates.{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=312}}{{sfn|Orel|1998|pp=631-633}} Romanian, Albanian and other languages sharing some common [[Morphology (linguistics)|morphological]] and [[Syntax|syntactic]] characteristics form together a supposed "[[Balkan Sprachbund|Balkan linguistic union]]".{{sfn|Augerot|2009|p=901}} These common features include the postposed [[definite article]]s<ref group="note">For example, ''o doamnă'' ("a lady") and ''doamna'' ("the lady"), ''un domn'' ("a gentleman") and ''domnul'' ("the gentleman") ''(Augerot 2009, p. 902.)''.</ref> and the merger of the [[dative case]] and [[possessive case]].{{sfn|Schulte|2009|p=235}}{{sfn|Mišeska Tomić|2006|p=27}} Whether they represent a common substrate language, or convergent development is still a matter of debate among linguists.{{sfn|Augerot|2009|p=901}}{{sfn|Schulte|2009|p=235}}

Hundreds of words that have presumably been inherited from Latin can only be traced back to hypotetical Latin words which were reconstructed based on their Romanian form.{{sfn|Wexler|1997|p=173}} Words of Latin origin were also borrowed from Slavic languages.<ref group="note">Including, ''[[colindă]]'' ("Christmas carol") and ''troiani'' ("snow drift").</ref>{{sfn|Wexler|1997|p=183}}{{sfn|Spinei|2009|pp=269-270}}

In addition to words of Latin or of possible substratum origin, loanwords make up more than 40% (according to certain estimations 60-80%){{sfn|Pană Dindelegan|2013|p=3}}{{sfn|Mallinson|1988|p=417}} of the Romanian vocabulary.{{sfn|Schulte|2009|p=239}} Linguist Gabriela P. Dindelegan underlines that contacts with other peoples has not modified the "Latin structure of Romanian" and the "non-Latin grammatical elements" borrowed from other languages were "adapted to and assimilated by the Romance pattern".{{sfn|Pană Dindelegan|2013|p=3}} No loanwords of [[East Germanic languages|East Germanic]] (Gothic or Gepid) origin have so far been proven.{{sfn|Augerot|2009|p=901}} In the Middle Ages, Slavic languages had a substantial influence on Romanian, but a significant number of words were borrowed from Turkic, Hungarian, Greek or German languages.{{sfn|Schulte|2009|pp=235-237}}{{sfn|Mallinson|1988|pp=413-415}}{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=343}}

The ratio of Slavic loanwords is still about 14%, although a strong "re-latinization" process has decreased their number since the 19th century.{{sfn|Schulte|2009|pp=241, 244}}{{sfn|Mallinson|1988|pp=415-417}} For instance, the number of Slavic borrowings exceeds that of the inherited terms in several semantic fields, including that of the natural environment{{sfn|Schulte|2009|p=250}} The names for most species of fish of the Danube<ref group="note">Including ''biban'' ("perch") [http://dexonline.ro/definitie/biban], ''cegă'' ("sterlet") [http://dexonline.ro/definitie/cegă], and ''plătică'' ("common bream") [http://dexonline.ro/definitie/plătică].</ref> and of a number of other animals living in Romania<ref group="note">For example, ''cârtiță'' ("mole") [http://dexonline.ro/definitie/cârtiță], ''dropie'' ("great bustard") [http://dexonline.ro/definitie/dropie], and ''râs'' ("lynx") [http://dexonline.ro/definitie/râs].</ref> are of Slavic origin.<ref name="Kopecký">{{Citation | last = Kopecký | first = Peter | title = ''Caractéristique lexicale de l'élément slave dans le vocabulaire roumain: Confrontation historique aux sédiments lexicaux turcs et grecs'' [=Lexical characteristics of the Slavic elements of the Romanians language: A historical comparison with the Turkic and Greek lexical layers] | journal = Ianua: Revista Philologica Romanica | volume = 5 | issue = | year = 2004–2005 | pages = 43–53 | url = http://www.romaniaminor.net/ianua/Ianua05/ianua05_04.pdf}}</ref> Linguists often attribute the development of about 10 phonological and morphological features of the Romanian language to Slavic influence, but there is no consensual view.{{sfn|Petrucci|1999|p=2}} For instance, contacts with Slavic-speakers allegedly contributed to the appearance of the [[semi-vowel]] [y] before the vowel [e] at the beginning of basic words and to the development of the [[vocative case]] in Romanian.{{sfn|Petrucci|1999|pp=49, 53, 101, 109}} Linguist Kim Schulte says, the significant common lexical items and the same morpho-syntactic structures of the Romanian and Bulgarian (and Macedonian) languages "indicates that there was a high decree of bilingualism in this mixed population".{{sfn|Schulte|2009|p=235}}

All neighboring peoples adopted a number of Romanian words connected to goat- and sheep-breeding.{{sfn|Nandris|1951|p=12}} Romanian loanwords are rare in standard Hungarian, but abound in its Transylvanian dialects.{{sfn|Szabó T.|1985|p=60}} In addition to place names and elements of the Romanian pastoral vocabulary, the Transylvanian Hungarians primarily adopted dozens of Romanian ecclesiastic and political terms to refer to specific Romanian institutions already before the mid-17th centuries.<ref group="note">For instance, ''[[Boyar of Fogaras|bojér]]'', ''[[Logofăt|logofét]]'', ''[[Eastern Christian monasticism|kalugyér]]'' and ''[[Wooden churches of Maramureș|beszerika]]''.</ref>{{sfn|Szabó T.|1985|pp=53, 57, 60-61}} The adoption of the Romanian terminology shows that the traditional Romanian institutions, which followed Byzantine patterns, significantly differed from their Hungarian counterparts.{{sfn|Szabó T.|1985|p=60}}

