Place names provide a significant proportion of modern knowledge of the extinct languages of South-eastern Europe.{{sfn|Fortson|2004|p=400}} Drobeta, Napoca, Porolissum, Sarmizegetusa and other settlements in "Dacia Traiana" bore names of local origin.{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=75}} Some towns preserved their ancient names<ref group="note">For instance, ''Poetovio'' ([[Ptuj]], [[Slovenia]]), and ''Siscia'' ([[Sisak]], [[Croatia]]) ''(Tóth 2004, p. 60.)''.</ref> in South-eastern Europe up until now, but the names of all Roman settlements attested in Roman Dacia in Antiquity disappeared.{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=292}}{{sfn|Tóth|1994|p=60}} The Romans adopted the native names of the main rivers<ref group="note">For instance, ''Crisia'' for the [[Criş River|Criş]], ''Maris(os)'' or ''Marissos'' for the [[Mureș River|Mureș]], ''*Samus'' for the [[Someș (river)|Someș]] and ''Tibisis'' for the [[Timiș River|Timiș]].</ref> and these names survived the Roman withdrawal.{{sfn|Vékony|2000|pp=77, 80}}{{sfn|Opreanu|2005|p=75}}{{sfn|Felecan|Felecan|2015|p=259}} Linguists Oliviu and Nicolae Felecan write that the names were "uninterruptedly transmitted" from the Dacians to the Romans, and then to the Dacoromans.{{sfn|Felecan|Felecan|2015|p=259}} [[Grigore Nandriș]] states that alone among the rivers in Dacia, the development of the name of the Criş from ancient ''Crisius'' would be in line with the phonetical evolution of Romanian.{{sfn|Nandris|1951|p=17}} Domnița Tomescu, Gottfried Schramm and other scholars say, the names of the rivers were preserved through a Slavic mediation.{{sfn|Tomescu|2009|p=2728}}{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=294}} The [[vowel shift]] from ''[a]'' to ''[u]'' or ''[o]'' experienced in the case of the rivers Mureş [<&nbsp;''Maris''], [[Olt River|Olt]] [<&nbsp;''Aluta''], and Someş [<&nbsp;''Samu(m)''] is attested in the development of the Slavic languages, but is alien to Romanian and other tongues spoken in their regions.<ref name='Makkai'>{{cite book|last = Makkai|first = László|title = Transylvania in the Medieval Hungarian Kingdom (896&ndash;1526), History of Transylvania, Volume I|publisher = Institute of History of the Hungarian Academy of Sciences|year = 2001|url = http://mek.niif.hu/03400/03407/html/58.html|isbn = 978-0-88033-479-2}}</ref> Linguist Marius Sala says that these phonetic changes featured the late phase of the "Daco-Thracian" language, so they are "a conclusive argument" in favor of the continuity theory.{{sfn|Sala|2005|p=17}} Schramm emphasizes that the ''[ʃ]'' ending of the modern names of the rivers could not be directly inherited from Latin, so they must have been transmitted from the local Dacians through Slavic mediation.{{sfn|Schramm|1997|pp=294-295}} Dunărea, the Romanian name of the Danube may have developed from a supposed{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=210}} [[Dacian language|Geto-Dacian]] ''*Donaris'' form.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dexonline.ro/definitie/Dunărea|publisher=dex-online.ro|title=Dunărea|work=Dicţionar explicativ al limbii române pe internet|date=2004–2008|author=|accessdate=14 October 2012}}</ref> However, this form is not attested in written sources.{{sfn|Vékony|2000|p=210}} Therefore, it is possible that the Romanians' ancestors in this case also adopted a Slavic name.{{sfn|Vékony|2000|pp=209-210}} Based on the [[Repedea River (Bistriţa)|Repedea]] name for the upper course of the [[Bistrița River (Someș)|Bistrița]] (both meaning "quick"), Nandris writes that translations from Romanian into Slavic could also create Romanian hydronyms.{{sfn|Nandris|1951|pp=17-18}}

More than a dozen of the tributaries of the large rivers had a name with probable Indo-European roots, suggesting a Dacian etymology.<ref group="note">For instance, the modern name of the river [[Ampoi]] may be connected to the Iranian words ''am'' ("with") and ''pel-/pal-'' ("color"), and the name of [[Săsar River]] is allegedly related to the Indo-European root ''*sar'' or ''*ser'' ("water", "to flow").</ref>{{sfn|Felecan|Felecan|2015|pp=257-258}} The Slavic mediation during the transmission of the names of some of them is obvious.<ref group="note">For example, the modern names of the rivers [[Cerna (Danube)|Cerna]] and [[Bârzava (Timiș)|Bârzava]] were transmitted from ancient ''Dierna'' and ''Bersobis'' through the mediation of a Slavic-speaking population.</ref>{{sfn|Tomescu|2009|p=2728}}{{sfn|Felecan|Felecan|2015|p=258}} The longer tributaries of the large rivers in Banat, Crişana and Transylvania which run through the most populated areas had modern names of German, Hungarian, Slavic or Turkic origin, which were also adopted by the Romanians.<ref name='Makkai'/> For instance, the tributaries of the [[Someșul Mic River]] bear Hungarian<ref group="note">Including, [[Căpuş River|Căpuş]], [[Nadăş River (Someş)|Nadăş]], and [[Fizeş River (Someş)|Fizeş]] [http://mek.niif.hu/03400/03407/html/61.html].</ref> or Slavic<ref group="note">[[Lonea River|Lonea]] and [[Lujerdiu River|Lujerdiu]] [http://mek.niif.hu/03400/03407/html/61.html].</ref> names,<ref name='Makkai'/> while other tributaries bear local Dacian names.<ref group="note">Including [[Bârzava (Timiș)|Bârzava]] and [[Nera (Danube)|Nera]].</ref> Many of the smallest rivers and streams<ref group="note">For instance, [[Baicu River (Iza)|Baicu]], Ghișa, Manciu.</ref> bear names of Romanian origin.{{sfn|Felecan|Felecan|2015|p=262}}{{sfn|Tomescu|2009|p=2728}}

Place names of Slavic<ref group="note">For instance, [[Câlnic, Alba|Câlnic]] ("muddy place"),  [[Straja, Alba|Straja]] ("guard"), [[Sumurducu]] ("stink"), and [[Ulciug]] ("highlanders") ''(Kristó 2003, p. 37.)''.</ref> or Hungarian<ref group="note">Including, [[Agârbiciu, Sibiu|Agârbiciu]] ("alder mountain"), [[Haşag]] ("linden hill"), [[Hosasău]] ("long valley"), [[Tioltiur]] ("Slavic guard"), and [[Verveghiu]] ("dried stream's valley") ''(Kristó 2003, pp. 107-108.)''.</ref> origin can be found in great number in medieval royal charters pertaining to Banat, Crișana, Maramureș, and Transylvania.{{sfn|Kristó|2003|p=37}} The names of Hungarian origin can be also found extensively in Moldavia, as a result of the Hungarian colonists settled during the medieval period.<ref name="Rădvan2011">{{cite book|author=Laurenţiu Rădvan|title=Orașele din Țările Române în Evul Mediu: (sfârșitul sec. al XIII-lea-începutul sec. al XVI-lea)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VNUKHbeLwpAC&pg=PA363|year=2011|publisher=Laurentiu Radvan|isbn=978-973-703-693-3|pages=363–}}</ref> In the mountains between the rivers [[Arieș River (Mureș)|Arieș]] and Mureș and in the territory the south of the [[Târnava Mare River]], the Romanians and the Transylvanian Saxons directly (without Hungarian mediation) adopted the Slavic place names.<ref name='The_Tót_Slavs_of_Transylvania'>{{cite book|last=Makkai |first=László |title=History of Transylvania, Volume I, Transylvania in the Medieval Hungarian Kingdom (896&ndash;1526), Transylvania's indigenous population at the time of the Hungarian Conquest: The "Tót" Slavs of Transylvania |publisher = Institute of History of the Hungarian Academy of Sciences|year = 2001|url = http://mek.niif.hu/03400/03407/html/62.html|isbn = 978-0-88033-479-2}}</ref> In almost all cases, when parallel Slavic-Hungarian or Slavic-German names are attested,<ref group="note">Including, the adoption of Bălgrad instead of Hungarian Gyulafehérvár, and of Straja instead of Őregyház.</ref> Romanians borrowed the Slavic forms, suggesting a long cohabitation of the Romanians and the Slavs or a close relationship between the two ethnic groups,<ref name='The_Tót_Slavs_of_Transylvania'/> maybe already before the arrival of the Hungarians.<ref>(Romanian) Tudor Sălăgean. [http://www.medievistica.ro/texte/tribuna/recenzii/ardealul%20timpuriu_Salagean.htm ''Review of Kristó, Gyula (2003). Early Transylvania (895-1324).'']</ref>

The earliest toponym of certain Romanian origin in the same regions ([[Sălaşu de Sus|Nucşoara]]) was recorded in 1359.{{sfn|Kristó|2003|pp=144-146}} River names of Slavic origin<ref group="note">For instance, [[Dâmbovița River|Dâmbovița]] and [[Glâmbocel River|Glâmbocel]] in Wallachia ''(Schramm 1997, p. 292.)''.</ref> can also be found in the regions east and south of the Carpathians,{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=292}} where [[Pecheneg]] or [[Cuman]] river names<ref group="note">For instance, tributaries of the [[Prut]] in Moldavia the name of which ends with ''-ui'' (including [[Bahlui River|Bahlui]], [[Covurlui River|Covurlui]], and [[Suhului River|Suhului]]) without doubt have a Turkic name ''(Spinei 2009, p. 318.)''.</ref> also abound.{{sfn|Tomescu|2009|p=2728}}{{sfn|Spinei|2009|pp=318-319}} On the other hand, the name of the [[Vlaşca County|Vlaşca]] region in Wallachia refers to a Romance-speaking community in Slavic environment.{{sfn|Makkai|1994|p=187}}

Place names of Latin origin abound in the region of [[Lake Shkodër]], along the rivers [[Drin (river)|Drin]] and [[Fan (river)|Fan]] and other territories to the north of the Viga Egnatia.{{sfn|Wilkes|1992|p=278}} Gottfried Schramm argues that the names of at least eight towns in the region,<ref group="note">Including [[Elassona]], [[Florina]], and [[Veria]] ''(Schramm 1997, p. 300.)''.</ref> likewise suggest the one-time presence of a Romance speaking population in their vicinity.{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=300}} Romanian place names can still be detected in Albania, Bulgaria, Greece, Montenegro and Serbia.{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=167}} For example, such names<ref group="note">For instance, Pasarel, [[Surdul]] [http://mek.niif.hu/03400/03407/html/60.html], [[Vakarel]] ''(Sălăgean 2005, p. 167.)''.</ref> are concentrated in the wider region of the river [[Vlasina (river)|Vlasina]] both in Bulgaria and Serbia,{{sfn|Schramm|1997|p=323}} and in Montenegro and the nearby territories.<ref group="note">For instance, the names of Mounts [[Durmitor]], [[Pirlitor]] and [[Visitor Mountain|Visitor]] ''(Sălăgean 2005, p. 167.)''.</ref>{{sfn|Sălăgean|2005|p=167}}

=== DNA / Paleogenetics ===
{{Primary sources|section|date=October 2018}}
{{split|Genetic studies on Romanians|date=May 2016}}
The use of genetic data to supplement traditional disciplines has now become mainstream.<ref>From molecular genetics to archaeogenetics. PNAS, Colin Renfrew, 2001</ref> Given the palimpsest nature of modern genetic diversity, more direct evidence has been sought from ancient DNA (aDNA)<ref>Pinhasi R, Thomas MG, Hofreiter M, Currat M, Burger J. The genetic history of Europeans. Trends in Genetics. 2012 Oct;28(10):496-505. PubMed {{PMID|22889475}}. Epub 2012/08/15. Eng</ref> Although data from southeastern Europe is still at an incipient stage, general trends are already evident. For example, it has shown that the Neolithic revolution imparted a major demographic impact throughout Europe, disproving the Mesolithic adaptation scenario in its pure form. In fact, the arrival of Neolithic farmers might have been in at least two "waves", as suggested by a study which analysed mtDNA sequences from Romanian Neolithic samples.<ref>Ancient DNA from South-East Europe Reveals Different Events during Early and Middle Neolithic Influencing the European Genetic Heritage. Hervella, et al (2015a)</ref> This study also shows that 'M_NEO' (''Middle Neolithic populations that lived in what is present-day Romania/Transylvania'') and modern populations from Romania are very close, in contrast with Middle Neolithic and modern populations from Central Europe.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|title=Ancient DNA from South-East Europe Reveals Different Events during Early and Middle Neolithic|journal = PLOS ONE|volume = 10|issue = 6|pages = e0128810|authors=Hervella, et al|last=|first=|date=|website=|dead-url=|year=2015b|pmc = 4460020|pmid = 26053041|doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0128810}}</ref> However, the samples extracted from Late Bronze Age DNA from Romania are farther from both of the previously mentioned.<ref>Hervella, et al (2015b), Figure 3.</ref> The authors have stated "Nevertheless, studies on more individuals are necessary to draw definitive conclusions."<ref>Hervella, et al (2015b), p. 12</ref> However, the study performed a "genetic analysis of a relatively large number of samples of Boian, Zau and Gumelniţa cultures in Romania (n = 41) (M_NEO)"<ref name=":0" />

Ancient DNA study<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.academia.edu/453597|title=Ancient DNA study on human fossils found in Costişa, Romania, dating from de Bronze Age|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> on human fossils found in Costişa, Romania, dating from de Bronze Age shows "close genetic kinship along the maternal lineage between the three old individuals from Costişa and some individuals found in other archeological sites dated from the Bronze and Iron Age. We also should note that the point mutations analyzed above are also found in Romanian modern population, suggesting that some old individuals from the human populations living on the Romanian land in the Bronze and Iron Age, could participate to a certain extent in the foundation of the Romanian genetic pool."

Another major demographic wave also occurred after 3000 BC from the steppe, postulated to be linked with the expansion of Indo-European languages.<ref>Massive migration from the steppe is a source for Indo-European languages in Europe</ref> Bronze and Iron Age samples from Hungary,<ref>Haak 2015</ref> Bulgaria<ref>Population Genomic Analysis of Ancient and Modern Genomes Yields New Insights into the Genetic Ancestry of the Tyrolean Iceman and the Genetic Structure of Europe</ref> and Romania,{{sfn|Cardos|Stoian|Miritoiu|Comsa|2004|pp=239-241}} however, suggest that this impact was less significant in Southeastern Europe than areas north of the Carpathians. In fact, in the abovementioned studies, the Bronze and Iron Age Balkan samples do not cluster with modern Balkan groups, but lie between [[Sardinians]] and other southwestern European groups, suggesting later phenomena (i.e. in Antiquity, Great Migration Period) caused shifts in population genetic structure. However, aDNA samples from southeastern Europe remain few, and only further sampling will allow a clear and diachronic overview of migratory and demographic trends.

No detailed analyses exist from the Roman and early medieval periods. Genome-wide analyses of extant populations show that intra-European diversity is a continuum (with the exception of groups like [[Finns]], [[Sami people|Sami]], [[Basques]] and [[Sardinians]]). Romanians cluster amidst their Balkan and East European neighbours. However, they generally lie significantly closer to Balkan groups (Serbs, Macedonians, Bulgarians) than to central and eastern Europeans like Hungarians, Czechs, Poles and Ukrainians, and many lie in the center of the Balkan cluster, near Albanians, Greeks, and Bulgarians, while many former Yugoslav populations like Serbs, Croats, and Slovenes may draw closer to central European West Slavs. On autosomal studies, genetic distance of some Romanian samples to some Italians, such as Tuscans, is greater than that of the distance to neighboring Balkan peoples, but can in some cases still be relatively close when considering the overall European population structure; this likely reflects mainly ancient or prehistoric population patterns rather than more recent ties due to linguistic relationships. Geography plays one of the most important roles in determining European population structure.<ref>Genetic Heritage of the Balto-Slavic Speaking Populations: A Synthesis of Autosomal, Mitochondrial and Y-Chromosomal Data. Kushniarevich et al, 2015</ref><ref>Correlation between Genetic and Geographic Structure in Europe. Lao et al. 2008</ref><ref>Genes mirror geography within Europe, Novembre et al. Nature. 2008 Nov 6; 456(7218): 98–101</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|pmc = 2735096|year = 2008|last1 = Novembre|first1 = J|title = Genes mirror geography within Europe|journal = Nature|volume = 456|issue = 7218|pages = 98–101|last2 = Johnson|first2 = T|last3 = Bryc|first3 = K|last4 = Kutalik|first4 = Z|last5 = Boyko|first5 = A. R|last6 = Auton|first6 = A|last7 = Indap|first7 = A|last8 = King|first8 = K. S|last9 = Bergmann|first9 = S|last10 = Nelson|first10 = M. R|last11 = Stephens|first11 = M|last12 = Bustamante|first12 = C. D|pmid = 18758442|doi = 10.1038/nature07331|bibcode = 2008Natur.456...98N}}</ref>

