{{Infobox weapon |name= Parang Chandong | image= ParangRayMears.JPG | image_size = 350 |caption= A Parang Chandong. |origin= [[Borneo]] ([[Sarawak|Sarawak, Malaysia]], [[West Kalimantan|West Kalimantan, Indonesia]], [[Brunei]]) |type= Chopper <!-- Type selection --> |is_bladed= Yes <!-- Service history --> |service= |used_by= [[Dayak people]] ([[Iban people]]) |wars= <!-- Production history --> |designer= |design_date= |manufacturer= |unit_cost= |production_date= |number= |variants= <!-- General specifications --> |spec_label= |weight= |length= approximately 40 - 50 cm |part_length= |width= |height= |diameter= |crew= <!-- Bladed weapon specifications --> |blade_type= Sheepsfoot point blade with a single convex edge |hilt_type= Wood |sheath_type= Wood |head_type= |haft_type= }}
'''Parang Chandong''' (also spelled as '''Parang Candong''', '''Parang Candung''', '''Duku Candong''' or '''Duku Candung''') is a traditional chopper used by the [[Dayak people]] ([[Iban people]]<ref>{{cite book|author=Augustine Anggat Ganjing, Jonathan Singki|title=Asas Ukiran Iban: Suatu Pengenalan|year=1991|publisher=Dewan Bahasa dan Pustaka|isbn=983-62-1398-8}}</ref>) of the [[Baram River]] in [[Borneo]].
The Parang Candung is also the primary weapon of Sari Panji, a character in the Rajé Ngalam tale of [[Sambas Regency]], [[West Kalimantan]], [[Indonesia]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Chairil Effendy|title=Teks Rajé Ngalam: Telaah Struktur Dan Resepsi|year=2001|publisher=Pusat Bahasa, Departemen Pendidikan Nasional|isbn=979-685-197-0}}</ref>
Recently in the west, the Parang Chandong was popularized by [[Raymond Mears]] and is sometimes referred to as '''Ray Mears Parang'''.
This parang is also not to be confused with the ''Candung'' in [[Lampung language]], which refers to another type of [[golok]] in [[Lampung]], [[Indonesia]].
==Description== The blade's edge is convex. The back is concave and curves towards the edge at the point. The centre of gravity lies near to the tip. The wooden scabbard's two parts are held together by means of rattan strips. The scabbard may be finely decorated, for instance with open-work carvings of floral motifs.<ref>{{cite book|author=Albert G Van Zonneveld|title=Traditional Weapons of the Indonesian Archipelago|url=https://www.amazon.com/Traditional-Weapons-Indonesian-Archipelago-Zonneveld/dp/9054500042/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1394869874&sr=8-1&keywords=Traditional+Weapons+of+the+Indonesian+Archipelago|year=2002|publisher=Koninklyk Instituut Voor Taal Land|isbn=90-5450-004-2}}</ref>
